WEBVTT
Kind: captions
Language: en

00:00:00.790 --> 00:00:04.000
&gt;&gt; From the Library of
Congress in Washington, DC.

00:00:19.190 --> 00:00:20.910
&gt;&gt; Douglas Caldwell: Good morning.

00:00:20.910 --> 00:00:22.260
&gt;&gt; Morning.

00:00:22.260 --> 00:00:24.670
&gt;&gt; Douglas Caldwell: My name is
Doug Caldwell, and I am Chair

00:00:24.670 --> 00:00:28.610
of the United States Board
on Geographic Names, or BGN.

00:00:28.610 --> 00:00:32.510
And on behalf of our
members and staff --

00:00:32.510 --> 00:00:36.110
[ Applause ]

00:00:36.110 --> 00:00:40.280
-- it is really a great pleasure
to welcome you here today

00:00:40.280 --> 00:00:45.280
as we celebrate our
125th Anniversary.

00:00:45.280 --> 00:00:50.250
Our geographic names are
more than mere words.

00:00:50.250 --> 00:00:56.130
They are, as Terrence Cole
once said, compact poetry.

00:00:56.130 --> 00:01:00.660
Geographic names are endlessly
fascinating in the stories

00:01:00.660 --> 00:01:06.200
that they tell and the
stories of their origins.

00:01:06.200 --> 00:01:13.230 position:56%
They reflect our cultural diversity,
our languages, our history,

00:01:13.230 --> 00:01:19.940
our environment, our
values, and our politics.

00:01:19.940 --> 00:01:24.090
Fortunately, geographic
names can also be confusing.

00:01:24.090 --> 00:01:30.270
There may be many names
for a single place.

00:01:30.270 --> 00:01:34.550
A single name may be
spelled many different ways.

00:01:34.550 --> 00:01:38.300
And many different places
may have the same name.

00:01:38.300 --> 00:01:43.100
And it is this confusion
that is at the root

00:01:43.100 --> 00:01:46.070
of the Board on Geographic Names.

00:01:46.070 --> 00:01:51.700
In early 1890 Thomas Mendenhall
from the Coast and Geodetic Survey

00:01:51.700 --> 00:01:54.430
and one of the founding
members complained

00:01:54.430 --> 00:01:57.410
about the confusion
caused by the lack

00:01:57.410 --> 00:02:01.090
of standardization of
names and spelling.

00:02:01.090 --> 00:02:06.940
He wrote to all of the federal
departments and he said,

00:02:06.940 --> 00:02:09.790
"You know, we have a problem.

00:02:09.790 --> 00:02:14.450
On our maps of your agencies
you are using different names

00:02:14.450 --> 00:02:16.050
for the same feature."

00:02:16.050 --> 00:02:20.570
And he said, "Even worse, I can see

00:02:20.570 --> 00:02:24.950
on a single map a single
agency uses different names

00:02:24.950 --> 00:02:26.750
for the same feature."

00:02:26.750 --> 00:02:29.260
Now I found this very
hard to believe,

00:02:29.260 --> 00:02:33.380
but it actually wasn't too
difficult to find an example.

00:02:33.380 --> 00:02:40.060
So this is an 1883 Army
reconnaissance map of Alaska.

00:02:40.060 --> 00:02:45.650
And it has the name Chilkat Inlet
in the title, spelled with a K,

00:02:45.650 --> 00:02:50.070
and Chilcat Inlet on the
map spelled with a C.

00:02:51.460 --> 00:02:57.550
So this is not exactly
what we wanted to see.

00:02:57.550 --> 00:02:59.740
So what happened was he

00:02:59.740 --> 00:03:04.830
with Lieutenant Richardson
Clover got together

00:03:04.830 --> 00:03:10.980
and called agencies
together to discuss

00:03:10.980 --> 00:03:15.070
and resolve conflicts
in geographic names.

00:03:15.070 --> 00:03:20.650
So this was a tremendous example
of interagency cooperation,

00:03:20.650 --> 00:03:25.490
starting in 1890, for the
benefit of the federal government.

00:03:27.430 --> 00:03:32.830
So on September 4th, 1890 -- it
was a day actually much like today;

00:03:32.830 --> 00:03:36.670
it was a nice fall day,
temperatures in the low 80s --

00:03:36.670 --> 00:03:40.850
President Benjamin Harrison
established the Board

00:03:40.850 --> 00:03:42.810
on Geographic Names.

00:03:42.810 --> 00:03:44.110
&gt;&gt; Hey, Doug.

