00:20:49.100 --> 00:20:50.650
&gt;&gt; Mark Monmonier:
Well good morning.

00:20:50.650 --> 00:20:51.950
Thank you for inviting me.

00:20:51.950 --> 00:20:57.450
It was an honor to be asked
to give the keynote address

00:20:57.450 --> 00:21:02.860
at a symposium recognizing the
125th anniversary of the founding

00:21:02.860 --> 00:21:05.490
of the U.S. Board on
Geographic Names.

00:21:05.490 --> 00:21:07.850
And particularly, I want
to thank Ralph Ehrenberg

00:21:07.850 --> 00:21:11.220
for making the initial
contact, and Doug Caldwell

00:21:11.220 --> 00:21:15.910
for handling arrangements
related to the program.

00:21:15.910 --> 00:21:19.840
And earlier draft of the
program suggested "The Power

00:21:19.840 --> 00:21:23.130
of Geographic Names" as
the title for my talk.

00:21:23.130 --> 00:21:25.040
I'm pleased that Doug
was enthusiastic

00:21:25.040 --> 00:21:27.720
when I proposed the title
that you see on the screen.

00:21:27.720 --> 00:21:31.450
I don't like the word power,
which has been overworked by those

00:21:31.450 --> 00:21:35.020
who see the map as a
mysterious irresistible force,

00:21:35.020 --> 00:21:37.210
which is simply not true.

00:21:37.210 --> 00:21:41.100
In my experience the term
leverage is far more appropriate.

00:21:41.100 --> 00:21:45.130
If you have the apparatus for
compiling and publishing maps,

00:21:45.130 --> 00:21:48.880
the map can enhance or
leverage that power.

00:21:48.880 --> 00:21:51.990
That said, cartography
in its use of symbols

00:21:51.990 --> 00:21:54.970
and words is a distinct
kind of rhetoric.

00:21:54.970 --> 00:22:00.200
And in some situations maps can
attract attention, lots of it,

00:22:00.200 --> 00:22:03.320
especially when geographic
names are involved.

00:22:03.320 --> 00:22:07.710 position:56%
Controversies over geographic names,
which became particularly prominent

00:22:07.710 --> 00:22:12.510
in the 20th century, show that
names on maps can be a forceful way

00:22:12.510 --> 00:22:15.600
of asserting ownership or control,

00:22:15.600 --> 00:22:20.280
or a way to denigrate a particular
group, perhaps unintentionally.

00:22:20.280 --> 00:22:24.900
Either situation invites
resistance, a pushback from people

00:22:24.900 --> 00:22:28.540
or organizations who
believe that other names,

00:22:28.540 --> 00:22:31.460
or names in some other
language or alphabet,

00:22:31.460 --> 00:22:35.490
are more appropriate or more just.

00:22:35.490 --> 00:22:36.980
More on this later.

00:22:36.980 --> 00:22:42.370
What are the roles
of geographic names?

00:22:42.370 --> 00:22:46.770
The most obvious role is to provide
a unique identifier for places

00:22:46.770 --> 00:22:52.180
and geographic features so that a
map user can assert unambiguously

00:22:52.180 --> 00:22:56.990
where he or she has
been or intends to go.

00:22:56.990 --> 00:23:01.480
This role of geographic names
underscores a key function of local

00:23:01.480 --> 00:23:05.590
or national naming authorities
like the Board on Geographic Names.

00:23:05.590 --> 00:23:10.080 position:56%
Namely, the key function of
avoiding potentially fatal confusion

00:23:10.080 --> 00:23:13.280
between features, including
confusion about where

00:23:13.280 --> 00:23:16.980
to send the rescue helicopter
or order up surveillance

00:23:16.980 --> 00:23:19.080
in advance of an airstrike.

00:23:19.080 --> 00:23:23.750
Although GPS has increased the
use of geographic coordinates

00:23:23.750 --> 00:23:28.300
in emergency response and military
contexts, many of us rely more

00:23:28.300 --> 00:23:30.330
on names than on numbers.

00:23:30.330 --> 00:23:37.320 position:56%
Much of the importance of geographic
names lies in the link they provide

00:23:37.320 --> 00:23:40.320
between map symbols
and everyday language,

00:23:40.320 --> 00:23:44.610
which in turn implies a need for
standards of grammar, spelling,

00:23:44.610 --> 00:23:48.530
syntax, and style, hence the
various rules that the Board

00:23:48.530 --> 00:23:51.260
on Geographic Names has crafted

00:23:51.260 --> 00:23:56.200
to avoid confusion and
needless complexity.

00:23:56.200 --> 00:24:00.170 position:56%
A chosen hegemonic language,
English rather than Native Hawaiian,

00:24:00.170 --> 00:24:04.970
for example, or Hebrew rather than
Arabic, can be a strong statement

00:24:04.970 --> 00:24:10.950
of territorial control, and thus
a potential source of resentment.

00:24:10.950 --> 00:24:13.920
And even when language,
per se, is not an issue,

00:24:13.920 --> 00:24:17.810
a geopolitical reference
like East Sea or Sea

00:24:17.810 --> 00:24:22.150
of Japan can trigger a resistance.

00:24:22.150 --> 00:24:26.560
Another role of geographic names
is to commemorate an individual,

00:24:26.560 --> 00:24:30.190
a people, an event, a
place in a distant land,

00:24:30.190 --> 00:24:32.360
or anything else with a name.

00:24:32.360 --> 00:24:37.060
Personal names can be particularly
problematic insofar as people

00:24:37.060 --> 00:24:39.870
like to leave their own mark,

00:24:39.870 --> 00:24:43.590
as when wealthy real estate
developers plaster their names

00:24:43.590 --> 00:24:49.920
on casinos and office towers,
or on mountains, bays, rivers,

00:24:49.920 --> 00:24:53.520
and lesser geographic features
if they could get away with it,

00:24:53.520 --> 00:24:57.030
which calls for a referee
acting in the public interest,

00:24:57.030 --> 00:25:01.280
a referee like the Board on
Geographic Names which collaborates

00:25:01.280 --> 00:25:06.170 position:56%
with a network of state-level boards
to circumvent potential conflict

00:25:06.170 --> 00:25:10.110
between people who think that
their favorite dead uncle is more

00:25:10.110 --> 00:25:12.630
deserving than your
favorite dead President.

00:25:12.630 --> 00:25:20.710
The rhetoric of geographic
names is a negotiate, reasoned,

00:25:20.710 --> 00:25:24.060
and inherently conservative
rhetoric, and a rhetoric

00:25:24.060 --> 00:25:25.540
that is resistant to change

00:25:25.540 --> 00:25:30.400
because too-frequent change can
be disruptive and confusing,

00:25:30.400 --> 00:25:32.570
not to mention expensive
if mapmakers want

00:25:32.570 --> 00:25:34.500
to keep their products up to date.

00:25:34.500 --> 00:25:39.880
An important point is that
geographic names are a public good,

00:25:39.880 --> 00:25:43.790
provided without private gain
to all members of society.

00:25:43.790 --> 00:25:47.870
Change might be warranted, but
it needs to be well thought out

00:25:47.870 --> 00:25:51.100
and perhaps responsive
to significant changes

00:25:51.100 --> 00:25:55.170
in public attitudes toward names
that have been publicly acceptable

00:25:55.170 --> 00:25:58.320
in the past but no longer are.

00:25:58.320 --> 00:26:03.480
By the 1960s, for instance, the
name Nigger Creek had become

00:26:03.480 --> 00:26:09.390
as offensively obsolete as Jim Crow
practices like segregated practices

00:26:09.390 --> 00:26:14.140
and race-based seating preferences
at lunch counters and on buses.

00:26:14.140 --> 00:26:20.200
At times civility demands that
some geographic names be changed.

00:26:20.200 --> 00:26:24.060
There is also a romantic
aspect to geographic names,

00:26:24.060 --> 00:26:28.700
as when they commemorate the
Revolutionary War heroes,

00:26:28.700 --> 00:26:33.310
Old World cities, or the
Ancient Mediterranean.

00:26:33.310 --> 00:26:37.860
And there's also a bit of romance
in bawdy or irreverent names

00:26:37.860 --> 00:26:41.240
like Whorehouse Meadow which
local historians committed

00:26:41.240 --> 00:26:45.460
to authenticity will defend
vigorously should anyone suggest

00:26:45.460 --> 00:26:47.310
replacing them.

00:26:47.310 --> 00:26:50.190
Indeed, there is no better
argument for the importance

00:26:50.190 --> 00:26:53.420
of geographic names than
the controversies that arise

00:26:53.420 --> 00:26:56.390
when someone, or some organization,

00:26:56.390 --> 00:27:00.370
or some government agency
proposes changing them.

00:27:01.460 --> 00:27:03.930
Let's examine some of
these controversies.

00:27:03.930 --> 00:27:08.560
Look first at the international
arena where names on maps,

00:27:08.560 --> 00:27:12.650
particularly names associated with
boundaries, are fighting words.

00:27:12.650 --> 00:27:16.050
Some names, like the territorial
control they represent,

00:27:16.050 --> 00:27:19.970
are so heinous that national
mapmakers refuse to put them

00:27:19.970 --> 00:27:23.720
on the map even when
it's abundantly clear

00:27:23.720 --> 00:27:26.430 position:56%
who controls a particular territory.

00:27:26.430 --> 00:27:28.800 position:56%
My first example is a map I acquired

00:27:28.800 --> 00:27:32.780
at an international
cartographic meeting in the 1970s,

00:27:32.780 --> 00:27:35.980
in a brochure distributed
by the Survey of Jordan

00:27:35.980 --> 00:27:40.510
which pointedly denied the
existence of the State of Israel.

00:27:40.510 --> 00:27:43.150
My apologies for the
sloppy colors here.

00:27:43.150 --> 00:27:48.050
I cannot locate the original
brochure, and when I had scanned

00:27:48.050 --> 00:27:49.390
and photoshopped this map

00:27:49.390 --> 00:27:54.520 position:56%
for publication decades ago I
needed only a black-and-white image.

00:27:54.520 --> 00:27:56.920
This is the best likeness
I could find.

00:27:56.920 --> 00:28:01.170
And despite the uneven hues,
it was too good to leave out.

00:28:01.170 --> 00:28:05.720
In this vein, Jordanian
cartographers erased Old Testament

00:28:05.720 --> 00:28:08.740 position:56%
names from the map of the Holy Land.

00:28:08.740 --> 00:28:12.130
And the Palestinian Liberation
Organization counterparts

00:28:12.130 --> 00:28:15.480
who produced a Palestinian
map series on the cheap

00:28:15.480 --> 00:28:19.140
by photocopying Israel's
one-to-100,000 scale topographic

00:28:19.140 --> 00:28:22.900
maps, replaced Hebrew
names with Arabic names,

00:28:22.900 --> 00:28:28.710 position:56%
and substituted the PLO logo for the
Survey of Israel copyright notice.

00:28:28.710 --> 00:28:32.860
By contrast, on Israeli
maps Arab towns and villages

00:28:32.860 --> 00:28:35.690
in Israel carry their Arabic names,

00:28:35.690 --> 00:28:38.600
which appear on official
Israeli maps.

00:28:38.600 --> 00:28:41.680
However, because naming places
can be an important part

00:28:41.680 --> 00:28:43.130
of nation building,

00:28:43.130 --> 00:28:46.810
Israeli cartographers have
assertively added ancient

00:28:46.810 --> 00:28:48.890
biblical names.

00:28:48.890 --> 00:28:50.830
One can find some intriguing
examples.

00:28:50.830 --> 00:28:53.440
I am going to show
you two map excerpts

00:28:53.440 --> 00:28:57.020
which are a study in
change and contrast.

00:28:57.020 --> 00:29:00.110
This first example is from
the Haifa sheet of the map

00:29:00.110 --> 00:29:04.240
of Palestine published
by the British in 1943.

00:29:04.240 --> 00:29:09.750 position:56%
The gridlines, which are a kilometer
apart, provide a sense of scale.

00:29:09.750 --> 00:29:13.080
The area is about 10
miles northeast of Haifa.

00:29:13.080 --> 00:29:17.310
Note the frame toward the lower
left which surrounds a small,

00:29:17.310 --> 00:29:20.850
[inaudible] like feature
marked by [inaudible].

00:29:21.990 --> 00:29:25.890
On the second example, from the
same quadrangle sheet published

00:29:25.890 --> 00:29:29.220
by the Survey of Israel in 1988,

00:29:29.220 --> 00:29:32.830
the name in the Roman
alphabet is generally similar.

00:29:32.830 --> 00:29:38.230
The first word, spelled T-A-L-L
on the British map and T-E-L

00:29:38.230 --> 00:29:41.700
on the Israel map,
means hill or ruin.

00:29:41.700 --> 00:29:45.290
What's noteworthy here is the
inscription of a Hebrew name

00:29:45.290 --> 00:29:48.160
to the left of the feature.

00:29:48.160 --> 00:29:54.460
Jump back to the 1943 Survey of
Palestine map, and note the frame

00:29:54.460 --> 00:29:58.900
around the village of Al-Birwa.

00:29:58.900 --> 00:30:01.650
Note also the two smaller
villages shown

00:30:01.650 --> 00:30:07.290
by dark splotches farther
south, Al-Damun and Ar Ruwais.

00:30:07.290 --> 00:30:15.680
And now look at the representations
on the 1988 Israeli map.

00:30:15.680 --> 00:30:17.930
Simply put, they're not there.

00:30:17.930 --> 00:30:21.250
And not because the
mapmaker suppressed them.

00:30:21.250 --> 00:30:24.790
The villages are gone, dismantled.

00:30:24.790 --> 00:30:30.470
This slide shows resistance to the
Israeli removal of Arab villages

00:30:30.470 --> 00:30:34.130
from the landscape
as well as from maps.

00:30:34.130 --> 00:30:37.640
It was posted on the
website Palestine Remembered.

00:30:37.640 --> 00:30:42.130
The inset map at the upper
right locates the district

00:30:42.130 --> 00:30:44.180
of Acre in the north of Israel.

00:30:44.180 --> 00:30:49.480
And the main map and its
key below show 26 villages.

00:30:49.480 --> 00:30:54.680 position:56%
This is an index map with links to
descriptions of the bygone villages.

00:30:54.680 --> 00:30:57.720
Note that the names are the links.

00:30:57.720 --> 00:30:59.730 position:56%
It is part of the electronic version

00:30:59.730 --> 00:31:02.700
of what has been called
the Arab map of Israel.

00:31:02.700 --> 00:31:08.550
The map has been replaced
by Google-type maps,

00:31:08.550 --> 00:31:12.030
some with a satellite background.

00:31:12.030 --> 00:31:15.800
You can zoom in and click on one of
the red pins to pull up information

00:31:15.800 --> 00:31:21.090
about bygone villages no longer
identified on present-day maps.

00:31:21.090 --> 00:31:25.010
The names remain in the database,
though, and can be plotted

00:31:25.010 --> 00:31:30.040
on demand by their coordinates.

00:31:30.040 --> 00:31:33.900
Let me turn to a controversy
prominent in our own national media

00:31:33.900 --> 00:31:38.360
in the 1990s when Korea,
still smarting from the pain

00:31:38.360 --> 00:31:44.120
of Japanese occupation from 1910
to 1945, objected to Western maps

00:31:44.120 --> 00:31:47.520
in which the body of water
directly east between Korea

00:31:47.520 --> 00:31:52.590
and Japan was labeled
the Sea of Japan.

00:31:52.590 --> 00:31:55.940
Media were lobbied to
substitute the name East Sea,

00:31:55.940 --> 00:32:00.710
which refers to is
location east of Korea.

00:32:00.710 --> 00:32:02.590 position:56%
Obviously the Koreans were not happy

00:32:02.590 --> 00:32:05.710
with the name Japan
immediately offshore.

00:32:05.710 --> 00:32:10.460 position:56%
To acknowledge Korean concerns,
many atlas publishers added East Sea

00:32:10.460 --> 00:32:15.750
in parentheses directly
below the better-known name.

00:32:15.750 --> 00:32:20.020
The National Geographic Society,
because its atlas was not yet due

00:32:20.020 --> 00:32:24.360
for a new edition, offered
this cut-out-and-paste-in patch

00:32:24.360 --> 00:32:26.570
on its website.

00:32:26.570 --> 00:32:31.670
It's still that way on
most cartographic websites.

00:32:31.670 --> 00:32:35.320
And the latest National
Geographic atlas uses both names

00:32:35.320 --> 00:32:39.060
with East Sea in parentheses.

00:32:39.060 --> 00:32:42.310
A similar controversy involving
countries on opposite sides

00:32:42.310 --> 00:32:47.010
of a large body of water is the
controversy over the Persian Gulf,

00:32:47.010 --> 00:32:51.290
the name favored by Iran,
but opposed by Saudi Arabia,

00:32:51.290 --> 00:32:54.500
which would prefer the
label Arabian Gulf.

00:32:54.500 --> 00:32:59.840
WorldAtlas.com is content with
the more widely-accepted name even

00:32:59.840 --> 00:33:03.900
for its map of the
United Arab Emirates.

00:33:03.900 --> 00:33:07.170
Google Maps has a clever,
21st century way

00:33:07.170 --> 00:33:09.010
of dealing with the conflict.

00:33:09.010 --> 00:33:12.730
When you or I ask to see its world
map only the name Persian Gulf

00:33:12.730 --> 00:33:14.030
is present.

00:33:14.030 --> 00:33:18.580
When you zoom in really close the
secondary name Arabian Gulf appears

00:33:18.580 --> 00:33:21.470
in parentheses.

00:33:21.470 --> 00:33:25.230
But because Google wants to avoid
having its web servers blocked

00:33:25.230 --> 00:33:29.750
by the web servers of Iran,
users with an IP address

00:33:29.750 --> 00:33:34.560
in Iran do not see
the name Arabian Gulf.

00:33:34.560 --> 00:33:37.030
But this accommodation
was worth the effort,

00:33:37.030 --> 00:33:40.000
reinforces the importance
of geographic names.

00:33:40.000 --> 00:33:44.590 position:56%
And west of the Gulf, I am told,
the name Persian Gulf is suppressed.

00:33:44.590 --> 00:33:49.740
To deal with issues like
this for U.S. government maps

00:33:49.740 --> 00:33:54.290 position:56%
and other publications, the
Foreign Names Committee of the Board

00:33:54.290 --> 00:33:59.880
on Geographic Names maintains
the searchable geonames database

00:33:59.880 --> 00:34:03.710
on the National Geospatial
Intelligence Agency website.

00:34:03.710 --> 00:34:07.780
A recent search for Arabian
Gulf revealed 14 substitutes

00:34:07.780 --> 00:34:10.750 position:56%
for the preferred name Persian Gulf.

00:34:10.750 --> 00:34:15.940
Note that the screen includes links
to two online mapping websites,

00:34:15.940 --> 00:34:18.600
Google Maps and MapQuest.

00:34:18.600 --> 00:34:23.700
Click on the Google Maps link, zoom
in a bit, and you get a red pin

00:34:23.700 --> 00:34:28.250
with both the preferred
and the secondary name.

00:34:28.250 --> 00:34:32.780
Click on the MapQuest link, and
no matter how closely you zoom

00:34:32.780 --> 00:34:35.770
in is an unnamed purple pin.

00:34:37.040 --> 00:34:39.760
Curious as to whether this
might have been a fluke,

00:34:39.760 --> 00:34:42.750
I tried to find the Arabian
Gulf with a direct search

00:34:42.750 --> 00:34:47.520
from Mapquest.com and got nothing.

00:34:47.520 --> 00:34:49.990
Searching for Germany
and then scrolling

00:34:49.990 --> 00:34:53.300
down to the southeast
led me to the conclusion

00:34:53.300 --> 00:34:55.430
that MapQuest does not label bodies

00:34:55.430 --> 00:34:59.220
of water smaller than
the Arabian sea.

00:34:59.220 --> 00:35:03.410
One way to deal with
vexatious toponyms.

00:35:03.410 --> 00:35:06.210
For a while, around 2012,

00:35:06.210 --> 00:35:11.230
Google Maps deliberately suppressed
the name Persian Gulf on its maps,

00:35:11.230 --> 00:35:16.670
but apparently adopted the present
policy after protests from Iran.

00:35:16.670 --> 00:35:18.560
This seems a good place to note

00:35:18.560 --> 00:35:25.570
that the Domestic Names Committee
has a policy whereby once named,

00:35:25.570 --> 00:35:29.420
a place cannot be un-named.

00:35:29.420 --> 00:35:34.620
Un-naming might have been a welcome
strategy for dealing with names

00:35:34.620 --> 00:35:36.390
like these, excerpted

00:35:36.390 --> 00:35:43.690
from geological survey maps
published in 1936, 1982, and 1986.

00:35:43.690 --> 00:35:48.450
Like most -- majority of toponyms,
they occur in sparsely-inhabited,

00:35:48.450 --> 00:35:51.940
relatively inaccessible areas.

00:35:51.940 --> 00:35:55.640
How these names wound up on
federal topographic maps is easy

00:35:55.640 --> 00:35:57.040
to understand.

00:35:57.040 --> 00:36:00.970
Topographers were sent into
the field and asked to measure

00:36:00.970 --> 00:36:04.990
and describe the landscape as
it was, at least to the extent

00:36:04.990 --> 00:36:08.380
that they could fit topographic
details, including place

00:36:08.380 --> 00:36:11.150
and feature names onto
a map published at one

00:36:11.150 --> 00:36:15.580
to 250,000, one to 62,500.

00:36:15.580 --> 00:36:19.340
In the pursuit of accuracy,
federal surveyors were required

00:36:19.340 --> 00:36:21.780
to ferret out local usage.

00:36:21.780 --> 00:36:25.700 position:56%
Whether a toponym might be offensive
to some people was immaterial.

00:36:25.700 --> 00:36:30.650
What mattered was whether a name
was applied and understood locally.

00:36:32.330 --> 00:36:38.390
Toponyms typically consist of two
parts, a generic and a specific.

00:36:38.390 --> 00:36:43.090
This slide illustrates that the
J word as a specific was applied

00:36:43.090 --> 00:36:47.760
to a variety of generics,
largely in the Western states,

00:36:47.760 --> 00:36:51.430
with a noteworthy concentration
in the Pacific Northwest.

00:36:51.430 --> 00:36:55.990 position:56%
Although J-word toponyms were more
common in the West than in the East,

00:36:55.990 --> 00:36:57.520
any correlation with a pattern

00:36:57.520 --> 00:37:02.330
of Japanese settlement
is faint at best.

00:37:02.330 --> 00:37:07.510
It's inevitable that the racial
enlightenment that swept the nation

00:37:07.510 --> 00:37:12.610
in the 1950s and 1960s would make
federal officials uncomfortable,

00:37:12.610 --> 00:37:16.020
if not mortified, by the
flagrant use of the N word

00:37:16.020 --> 00:37:18.460
on the nation's topographic maps.

00:37:18.460 --> 00:37:20.430
As best I can discern,

00:37:20.430 --> 00:37:23.600
the Washington establishment
was largely ignorant

00:37:23.600 --> 00:37:28.980 position:56%
of the implied federal
endorsement of the N word until 1962

00:37:28.980 --> 00:37:30.610 position:56%
when Secretary -- when the Secretary

00:37:30.610 --> 00:37:34.520
of the Interior Stuart
Udall, ordered its removal.

00:37:34.520 --> 00:37:39.210 position:56%
USGS mapmakers responded by
changing all instances of the N word

00:37:39.210 --> 00:37:44.610
to negro, which was considered
acceptable at the time.

00:37:44.610 --> 00:37:48.430
Unfortunately, these
toponyms were replaced only

00:37:48.430 --> 00:37:53.030
when a map sheet was revised, which
in many cases meant replacement

00:37:53.030 --> 00:37:55.020
of the 15-minutes series

00:37:55.020 --> 00:37:57.550
by the more-details
seven-and-1/2-minute series

00:37:57.550 --> 00:37:59.860
over the next 20 years.

00:37:59.860 --> 00:38:09.640
The only other instance of blanket
renaming was initiated in 1974

00:38:09.640 --> 00:38:15.020
when USGS mapmakers were ordered
to replace Jap with Japanese.

00:38:15.020 --> 00:38:18.980
If you're curious about the
incidence of these toponyms,

00:38:18.980 --> 00:38:22.680
they are now online in
the web version of GNIS,

00:38:22.680 --> 00:38:25.420
the geographic names
information system.

00:38:25.420 --> 00:38:30.540
GNIS was started as a
one-state pilot project in 1976.

00:38:30.540 --> 00:38:34.110
Its earliest phase included
the capture of all toponyms

00:38:34.110 --> 00:38:38.890
on then-current federal quadrangle
maps, a boon for mapmakers

00:38:38.890 --> 00:38:40.660
and anyone else concerned

00:38:40.660 --> 00:38:43.950
with racially-offensive
place and feature names.

00:38:43.950 --> 00:38:49.400
The GNIS website now makes it
easy to identify offensive names

00:38:49.400 --> 00:38:52.980
which might survive in a
database as so-called variants,

00:38:52.980 --> 00:38:56.790
a designation that includes
obsolete names as well

00:38:56.790 --> 00:38:59.900
as non-standard spellings.

00:38:59.900 --> 00:39:05.490
This map shows the instance by
state of toponyms with the N word

00:39:05.490 --> 00:39:07.540
or two similar spellings.

00:39:07.540 --> 00:39:12.670
It is interesting to note that few
of the N-word pejoratives occur

00:39:12.670 --> 00:39:15.020
in the Southeast, the
part of the country

00:39:15.020 --> 00:39:16.810
with the most violent resistance

00:39:16.810 --> 00:39:20.490
to the Civil Rights
Movement in the 1960s.

00:39:20.490 --> 00:39:23.630
The source for this map
is the Omni Gazetteer,

00:39:23.630 --> 00:39:30.610
a multi-volume reference
work published in 1991

00:39:30.610 --> 00:39:35.650
and based largely on GNIS.

00:39:36.810 --> 00:39:41.460
This more complete cartographic
summary is based on a snapshot

00:39:41.460 --> 00:39:46.600
of the GNIS database
obtained in 2003.

00:39:46.600 --> 00:39:52.040
The large number of N-word
pejoratives reflects what USGS

00:39:52.040 --> 00:39:58.060
called phase-two names compilation,
a piecemeal process contracted

00:39:58.060 --> 00:40:01.080
out on a state-by-state
basis and designed

00:40:01.080 --> 00:40:03.860
to identify additional
named features,

00:40:03.860 --> 00:40:06.060
not just those on federal maps.

00:40:06.060 --> 00:40:12.430
As the title indicates, these
names are mostly variants.

00:40:13.480 --> 00:40:17.870
Also based on GNIS, this
map shows the distribution

00:40:17.870 --> 00:40:20.210
of toponyms containing negro.

00:40:20.210 --> 00:40:24.530
As of mid-2003 none of
these were variants.

00:40:24.530 --> 00:40:31.050
Some, but not all of them, reflect
the blanket renaming of the 1960s.

00:40:31.050 --> 00:40:35.870
By century's end negro had become
less acceptable as a substitute,

00:40:35.870 --> 00:40:41.550
but BGN rules rejected cumbersome
substitutes like African-American

00:40:41.550 --> 00:40:45.300
or the utterly generic B-L-A-C-K.

00:40:45.300 --> 00:40:48.420
Replacement names had to
be vetted individually

00:40:48.420 --> 00:40:54.000
by the locally-initiated process
used for un-named features.

00:40:59.150 --> 00:41:04.140
This slide shows the progression
of feature names for a place

00:41:04.140 --> 00:41:08.110
in Upstate New York along
the Lake Ontario shoreline

00:41:08.110 --> 00:41:10.660
between Rochester and Oswego.

00:41:10.660 --> 00:41:13.320
According to the town
historian, the original name,

00:41:13.320 --> 00:41:17.080 position:56%
shown in the top frame from a
topographic quadrangle map published

00:41:17.080 --> 00:41:21.120
in 1943, reflects the
place's role as a station

00:41:21.120 --> 00:41:23.340
on the Underground Railroad.

00:41:23.340 --> 00:41:25.900
Someone at USGS apparently
recognized it

00:41:25.900 --> 00:41:29.490
as inappropriate before
the Udall edict.

00:41:29.490 --> 00:41:32.220
The redacted version
in the middle frame is

00:41:32.220 --> 00:41:35.820
from a USGS map published in 1953.

00:41:35.820 --> 00:41:37.980
The lower frame is from a
New York State Department

00:41:37.980 --> 00:41:41.210 position:56%
of Transportation
seven-and-1/2-minute planometric map

00:41:41.210 --> 00:41:43.580
published in 1977.

00:41:43.580 --> 00:41:47.040
I was unable to track down
the origin of the name Graves.

00:41:47.040 --> 00:41:53.470
Doug, when people here reviewed
my slides, somebody looked

00:41:53.470 --> 00:42:00.630
into the geonames database,
and Graves Point is not there.

00:42:00.630 --> 00:42:04.140
The only thing I can figure
is there is a road that goes

00:42:04.140 --> 00:42:09.240
up there that's called Graves Point
Road, and DOT, being the Department

00:42:09.240 --> 00:42:10.960
of Transportation, I
guess, took it from that.

00:42:10.960 --> 00:42:15.030
And maybe somebody trying to sell
building lots up there figured

00:42:15.030 --> 00:42:17.000
that that might be more apropos.

00:42:20.460 --> 00:42:24.430
The most contentious renaming
issue involves the word squaw,

00:42:24.430 --> 00:42:29.720
deemed not amenable
to blanket replacement

00:42:29.720 --> 00:42:32.190
with Indian woman or clan mother.

00:42:32.190 --> 00:42:33.920 position:56%
Like feature names containing negro,

00:42:33.920 --> 00:42:37.170
names with squaw must be
dealt with individual.

00:42:37.170 --> 00:42:39.650
This map, which they
made about 10 years ago,

00:42:39.650 --> 00:42:42.230
suggests the extent of the problem.

00:42:42.230 --> 00:42:47.510
Here's a choropleth map which
reports the same data as the ratio.

00:42:47.510 --> 00:42:51.590
Each state's count of
S-word toponyms was divided

00:42:51.590 --> 00:42:57.010
by its total number of named
features and multiplied by 100,000

00:42:57.010 --> 00:43:01.590
to provide a more readable key.

00:43:01.590 --> 00:43:05.910
Note that the highest rates
are in Idaho and Oregon.

00:43:05.910 --> 00:43:11.840
For whatever reason, the lowest
rates are in the Southeast.

00:43:11.840 --> 00:43:18.160
Minnesota's low rate, as of
2002, reflects a concerted effort

00:43:18.160 --> 00:43:23.110
to replace S-word toponyms
with acceptable substitutes.

00:43:24.240 --> 00:43:28.770
Although states and localities can
change toponyms their actions have

00:43:28.770 --> 00:43:32.430
no impact on federal maps and
databases unless the Board

00:43:32.430 --> 00:43:35.310
on Geographic Names
approves the change.

00:43:35.310 --> 00:43:38.380
Typically the State
Names Board must approve,

00:43:38.380 --> 00:43:42.950
and tribal officials are also
consulted for names on tribal lands

00:43:42.950 --> 00:43:46.150
or other areas in which the
tribe might have an interest.

00:43:46.150 --> 00:43:48.890
As this list of requirements
indicates,

00:43:48.890 --> 00:43:52.740
the process is bureaucratic,
but hardly daunting.

00:43:52.740 --> 00:43:57.340 position:56%
How the nation deals with its
S-word toponyms will be a noteworthy

00:43:57.340 --> 00:44:01.780
concern for historians of
21st century cartography.

00:44:01.780 --> 00:44:05.120
Will political pressure
expedite the process?

00:44:05.120 --> 00:44:08.710
Will Native American leaders
give the issue a lower place

00:44:08.710 --> 00:44:10.780
on their agenda?

00:44:10.780 --> 00:44:14.690
Will majority public opinion
eventually find the word

00:44:14.690 --> 00:44:21.320
so offensive that public officials
at all levels are required to act?

00:44:21.320 --> 00:44:26.020
Will businesses cooperate or resist
when an S-word toponym refers

00:44:26.020 --> 00:44:30.970
to a branded tourist
destination like Squaw Valley?

00:44:30.970 --> 00:44:35.090
Native Americans are offended
by other kinds of names.

00:44:36.190 --> 00:44:39.390
For instance, the name Mount
McKinley for the tallest name

00:44:39.390 --> 00:44:43.530
in Alaska, also the tallest
mountain in North America.

00:44:43.530 --> 00:44:47.900
The correct name, which the Board
on Geographic Names recognizes,

00:44:47.900 --> 00:44:51.200
or would like to have
recognized, is Denali,

00:44:51.200 --> 00:44:54.080
an Athabaskan word
for "the high one."

00:44:54.080 --> 00:44:58.670
The peak had several
names, including Denali,

00:44:58.670 --> 00:45:03.850
in 1896 when William
Dickey, an Alaskan prospector

00:45:03.850 --> 00:45:07.850
and Princeton graduate, proposed
naming it for William McKinley

00:45:07.850 --> 00:45:12.930
who had recently received the
Republican presidential nomination.

00:45:12.930 --> 00:45:19.050
In Dickey's mind, McKinley's strong
point was his spirited defense

00:45:19.050 --> 00:45:20.350
of the gold standard.

00:45:20.350 --> 00:45:25.840
In 1897 Dickey mentioned the
name Mount McKinley eight times

00:45:25.840 --> 00:45:29.680
in a short article he wrote for
"National Geographic" magazine,

00:45:29.680 --> 00:45:33.510
an article somehow
interpreted as an endorsement.

00:45:33.510 --> 00:45:38.530 position:56%
The name was widely accepted by
1901 when McKinley was assassinated,

00:45:38.530 --> 00:45:41.260
and a grieving citizenry
began plastering the name

00:45:41.260 --> 00:45:45.300
of our 25th President on
high schools nationwide,

00:45:45.300 --> 00:45:48.560
as fans of "Glee" are well aware.

00:45:48.560 --> 00:45:55.230
Even so, Hudson Stuck, Episcopal
Archdeacon of the Yukon,

00:45:55.230 --> 00:45:58.370
preferred the name Denali.

00:45:58.370 --> 00:46:03.610
In 1913 Stuck became the first
person to reach the summit

00:46:03.610 --> 00:46:07.270
and described this accomplishment
in his book "The Ascent

00:46:07.270 --> 00:46:10.200
of Denali" published
the following year.

00:46:10.200 --> 00:46:14.330
Athabaskans had no voice on the
issue, nor did white Alaskans

00:46:14.330 --> 00:46:17.860
who pointed out that McKinley
had never visited the territory,

00:46:17.860 --> 00:46:20.980
which was accorded
statehood in 1959.

00:46:20.980 --> 00:46:26.390
Calls for renaming the peak
persisted, including a resolution

00:46:26.390 --> 00:46:28.490
by the Alaskan legislature.

00:46:28.490 --> 00:46:31.890
Finally in 1980, the National
Park Service changed the name

00:46:31.890 --> 00:46:37.640
of Mount McKinley National Park to
Denali National Park and Preserve.

00:46:37.640 --> 00:46:42.240
The Park Service can rename its
facilities without BGN approval

00:46:42.240 --> 00:46:46.080
if Congress consents, as it did.

00:46:46.080 --> 00:46:50.380
All the same, the name Mount
McKinley stuck for over a century

00:46:50.380 --> 00:46:54.090
because a single member of
Congress could block a name change

00:46:54.090 --> 00:46:58.620 position:56%
by the Board on Geographic Names,
because one of its bylaws precludes,

00:46:58.620 --> 00:47:02.370
quote, a decision on a
name or its application

00:47:02.370 --> 00:47:06.040 position:56%
if the matter is being considered
by the Congress of the United States

00:47:06.040 --> 00:47:08.930
or the Executive Branch, end quote.

00:47:08.930 --> 00:47:14.610
For a long time the obstacle was
Congressman Ralph Regula whose

00:47:14.610 --> 00:47:18.590
district included McKinley's
hometown, Canton, Ohio.

00:47:18.590 --> 00:47:21.620
Shortly after a new
Congress was sworn in,

00:47:21.620 --> 00:47:26.050
Regula would introduce a bill
to keep the name Mount McKinley,

00:47:26.050 --> 00:47:30.160
basically, as Ralph tells me,
by threatening the USDS budget.

00:47:30.160 --> 00:47:34.160
Even though these bills went
nowhere they blocked any action

00:47:34.160 --> 00:47:36.100
by the federal Board.

00:47:36.100 --> 00:47:37.730
Now as we know -- well know,

00:47:37.730 --> 00:47:42.720
the situation changed abruptly
last month, and for the good

00:47:42.720 --> 00:47:45.780
and long overdue, I'd say.

00:47:45.780 --> 00:47:47.910
Another names controversy related

00:47:47.910 --> 00:47:51.610
to a murdered President
occurred in 1963.

00:47:51.610 --> 00:47:54.200
In the week after the
Kennedy assassination,

00:47:54.200 --> 00:47:56.650
when the new President
Lyndon Johnson decided

00:47:56.650 --> 00:48:00.710
to put Kennedy's name
on Cape Canaveral.

00:48:00.710 --> 00:48:03.120
Johnson was a forceful politician,

00:48:03.120 --> 00:48:06.300
noted for having rammed the
Civil Rights Act through Congress

00:48:06.300 --> 00:48:09.400
and sending a half
million troops to Vietnam.

00:48:09.400 --> 00:48:11.810
Florida residents were outraged.

00:48:11.810 --> 00:48:14.390
Because Kennedy was from
Massachusetts, they asked,

00:48:14.390 --> 00:48:17.600
why not rename it --
why not rename Cape Cod?

00:48:17.600 --> 00:48:24.240 position:56%
Moreover, Canaveral was an old name,
having made its cartographic debut

00:48:24.240 --> 00:48:31.190
in 1564 on a map by French
artist/explorer Jacques le Moyne.

00:48:31.190 --> 00:48:34.960
In 1973 the Board on Geographic
names accepted Florida's

00:48:34.960 --> 00:48:38.850
recommendation that the
original name be restored.

00:48:38.850 --> 00:48:41.910
By general agreement, the
prominent NASA facility

00:48:41.910 --> 00:48:45.960
on the Cape remained the
Kennedy Space Flight Center.

00:48:45.960 --> 00:48:50.950
Another consequence was the
establishment in 1984 of a rule

00:48:50.950 --> 00:48:54.860
that banned renaming
geographic features after people

00:48:54.860 --> 00:48:56.570
who had been dead less
than one year.

00:48:56.570 --> 00:49:02.300
In 1995 the waiting period
was increased to five years.

00:49:02.300 --> 00:49:08.280
The five-year rule caused
conflict with another state in 2003

00:49:08.280 --> 00:49:12.090
when Arizona Governor Janet
Napolitano convinced the State

00:49:12.090 --> 00:49:18.850
Board, strong-arming them, to
rename Squaw Peak near Phoenix

00:49:18.850 --> 00:49:22.840
for Lori Piestewa, the first
female Native American soldier

00:49:22.840 --> 00:49:24.440
to die in combat.

00:49:24.440 --> 00:49:28.090
Napolitano saw Piestewa's
death as an opportunity

00:49:28.090 --> 00:49:30.450
to expunge a prominent
derogatory name

00:49:30.450 --> 00:49:35.900
that had recently caught the ire
of Native American activists.

00:49:35.900 --> 00:49:40.250
Napolitano was no Lyndon Johnson,
and the Federal Board held fast

00:49:40.250 --> 00:49:44.930
until 2008 when the five-year
waiting period had passed.

00:49:44.930 --> 00:49:49.680
Hawaii was another state in which
indigenous people resisted the

00:49:49.680 --> 00:49:52.170
official treatment
of geographic names.

00:49:52.170 --> 00:49:56.010
The issue was not so much the
names themselves, but the system

00:49:56.010 --> 00:50:03.070
of Romanization that conspicuously
suppressed two diacritical marks,

00:50:03.070 --> 00:50:05.350
the macron and the glottal stop,

00:50:05.350 --> 00:50:08.720
both of which signify
important tonal differences.

00:50:08.720 --> 00:50:12.770
The macron is a short bar above
a letter, usually a vowel.

00:50:12.770 --> 00:50:16.550
Here's a USGS map showing a
name rendered with a macron.

00:50:16.550 --> 00:50:21.470
And here is the same feature in
an excerpt from an earlier edition

00:50:21.470 --> 00:50:23.640
of the same quadrangle map.

00:50:23.640 --> 00:50:27.560
This earlier Romanization
affects other letters as well

00:50:27.560 --> 00:50:31.300
and shows two words, not one.

00:50:31.300 --> 00:50:37.420
This slide from a 1998 map has
two examples of the glottal stop

00:50:37.420 --> 00:50:41.040
which Hawaiians write as
a single open quote mark.

00:50:41.040 --> 00:50:45.930
In 1995 the Board on
Geographic Names relaxed the rule

00:50:45.930 --> 00:50:49.980
that had prohibited diacritical
marks used in Native languages

00:50:49.980 --> 00:50:54.080
in Alaska and Hawaii, and over the
next 10 years the federal Board

00:50:54.080 --> 00:50:58.530
approved several thousand
revised Hawaiian names in time

00:50:58.530 --> 00:51:04.920
for a major revision of
large-scale USGS topographic maps.

00:51:04.920 --> 00:51:08.940
Here's the same feature on
an earlier map from 1954.

00:51:08.940 --> 00:51:13.420
Note that the two glottal stops
have been accommodated awkwardly

00:51:13.420 --> 00:51:16.720
by blank spaces.

00:51:16.720 --> 00:51:21.310
Another kind of geographic name
that might evoke a call for change,

00:51:21.310 --> 00:51:25.250
