In 2005 the World Bank put
out a very interesting report

01:07:42.220 --> 01:07:45.840
and indicated that at
least 50% of city streets

01:07:45.840 --> 01:07:50.910
in Sub-Saharan Africa had no
names, and therefore, no addresses.

01:07:50.910 --> 01:07:54.670
And this was because the centers
of the city had become more dense,

01:07:54.670 --> 01:07:58.430
the urban areas had expanded,
and names had not kept up.

01:07:58.430 --> 01:08:01.750
Now this is very difficult
for individual identity,

01:08:01.750 --> 01:08:05.500
for bank accounts, or postal
delivery, or anything like that,

01:08:05.500 --> 01:08:10.830
for gathering taxes, for urban
planning, for following epidemics.

01:08:10.830 --> 01:08:14.010
With no names and addresses
this is a difficulty.

01:08:14.010 --> 01:08:18.120
So the World Bank did finance
several Sub-Saharan African

01:08:18.120 --> 01:08:20.830
countries to set up
street addressing,

01:08:20.830 --> 01:08:23.720
and associated databases, and maps.

01:08:23.720 --> 01:08:26.820
To start with they
suggested numbering systems,

01:08:26.820 --> 01:08:31.160
which you can imagine is not as
controversial as putting names.

01:08:31.160 --> 01:08:34.050
And then these could
be augmented later.

01:08:34.050 --> 01:08:35.600
So for instance, in Yaounde

01:08:35.600 --> 01:08:42.330
in Cameroon this first one
would be one of six zones.

01:08:42.330 --> 01:08:45.920
This is zone one, street number 74.

01:08:45.920 --> 01:08:50.350
In this case we've got a name added
as well as the zone 2 reference.

01:08:50.350 --> 01:08:53.490
And this one shows one of
each, one without a name,

01:08:53.490 --> 01:08:55.610 position:56%
and one where a name has been added.

01:08:55.610 --> 01:08:59.840
So that was the approach
that was taken on that.

01:08:59.840 --> 01:09:02.880
If I can go back to the
level of national boards,

01:09:02.880 --> 01:09:07.270
most exist with some sort of
legal framework, an act maybe.

01:09:07.270 --> 01:09:10.480
And in the older acts
usually it was just described

01:09:10.480 --> 01:09:13.280
in a technical way
about approval of names.

01:09:13.280 --> 01:09:17.120
But in newer boards, as
in Burkina Faso recently,

01:09:17.120 --> 01:09:20.850
there has been much more about
the idea of cultural heritage,

01:09:20.850 --> 01:09:24.720
of conserving face names, or
preserving toponomic heritage

01:09:24.720 --> 01:09:26.810
of culture and of language.

01:09:26.810 --> 01:09:32.040
The same thing in Tunisia,
again in 2013 they talked

01:09:32.040 --> 01:09:36.550
about national toponomic heritage,
of preserving the specifics

01:09:36.550 --> 01:09:39.420
of Arabic, of the Tunisian
form of Arabic,

01:09:39.420 --> 01:09:44.240
ensuring that studies be undertaken
in -- on geographical names.

01:09:45.430 --> 01:09:50.560
So in fact, toponyms do
link man to the land.

01:09:50.560 --> 01:09:53.210
They are points of reference.

01:09:53.210 --> 01:09:56.430
They are bearers of our
history and our language

01:09:56.430 --> 01:09:59.420
and carriers of our identity.

01:09:59.420 --> 01:10:03.120
So this brings up interesting
questions.

01:10:03.120 --> 01:10:08.050 position:56%
The mantra in the past, particularly
from cartographers was one name

01:10:08.050 --> 01:10:10.410
for one feature, or university.

01:10:10.410 --> 01:10:12.710
And Nameless Cove is
in Newfoundland,

01:10:12.710 --> 01:10:15.760
so don't take offense from that.

01:10:15.760 --> 01:10:17.420
But it brings now the question

01:10:17.420 --> 01:10:22.150
of should there be multiple
names recognized in the languages

01:10:22.150 --> 01:10:25.710
of the country, reflecting,
perhaps reality,

01:10:25.710 --> 01:10:27.410
if you like to put it that way.

01:10:27.410 --> 01:10:32.520
This is in Norway with
Norwegian Sami language

01:10:32.520 --> 01:10:34.290
and [inaudible], or finish.

01:10:34.290 --> 01:10:38.430
There's another example in
Slovenia with the Italian added,

01:10:38.430 --> 01:10:42.700
and there are many more examples
we could give of multiple naming.

01:10:42.700 --> 01:10:46.550
This is New Zealand where
names might be in [inaudible],

01:10:46.550 --> 01:10:48.390
or they might be in English.

01:10:48.390 --> 01:10:50.880
Or in the two examples
shown there are various ways

01:10:50.880 --> 01:10:54.120
of having combinations of names.

01:10:54.120 --> 01:10:57.420
This, of course, does bring
questions for cartographers.

01:10:57.420 --> 01:11:01.590
And this is in northern Finland
with three names for Inari,

01:11:01.590 --> 01:11:02.890
although I just learned last week

01:11:02.890 --> 01:11:05.650
that there are now
five names for Inari.

01:11:05.650 --> 01:11:10.430
And the Finnish way of
handling this is you either

01:11:10.430 --> 01:11:13.990
on a map show all the names,
or you omit the altogether.

01:11:13.990 --> 01:11:17.270
You do not just pick
one or two of them out.

01:11:17.270 --> 01:11:20.450
And in Canada this year we
have increased the names

01:11:20.450 --> 01:11:23.040
for the Mackenzie River,
and we now have seven names

01:11:23.040 --> 01:11:26.550
in the local languages
of the Mackenzie Valley.

01:11:26.550 --> 01:11:28.840
Still have to figure out
how we're going to deal

01:11:28.840 --> 01:11:31.640
with this on maps, incidentally.

01:11:31.640 --> 01:11:35.790
I'd like now to look at something
about the sort of time frame

01:11:35.790 --> 01:11:39.360
when national authorities
have been set up.

01:11:39.360 --> 01:11:43.210
The United States Board,
as you know, from 1890,

01:11:43.210 --> 01:11:47.330
was the first national board
established in the world.

01:11:47.330 --> 01:11:51.420
Canada was shortly after that, for
similar reasons, the settlement

01:11:51.420 --> 01:11:57.320
in the West, and the confusion
of names that were taking place.

01:11:57.320 --> 01:12:00.150
Four other countries,
Denmark, Iceland, New Zealand,

01:12:00.150 --> 01:12:02.610
and Ireland all had
boards established

01:12:02.610 --> 01:12:05.110
by the end of the Second World War.

01:12:05.110 --> 01:12:08.510
And now in our sort of latest
figures we have got some 80

01:12:08.510 --> 01:12:11.310
countries that have
national authorities.

01:12:11.310 --> 01:12:14.020
And this would mean, again,

01:12:14.020 --> 01:12:17.440
dealing with domestic names
rather than with foreign names.

01:12:17.440 --> 01:12:20.610
Most recent of these are Saudi
Arabia, and Burkina Faso,

01:12:20.610 --> 01:12:23.820
and Tunisia that I
mentioned, Sri Lanka,

01:12:23.820 --> 01:12:27.610
the Foroyar area of
Denmark, and so on.

01:12:27.610 --> 01:12:31.890
But we do have to be fair on this,
even though they're established

01:12:31.890 --> 01:12:36.400
by law, there are some boards that
are clearly not really functional

01:12:36.400 --> 01:12:40.910
at the present time, to
be encouraged, obviously.

01:12:40.910 --> 01:12:47.050
If we look at this on a basis of a
map, the green areas are countries

01:12:47.050 --> 01:12:49.370
that have national
names authorities.

01:12:49.370 --> 01:12:54.110 position:56%
The purple-y color are the ones that
without national names authorities.

01:12:54.110 --> 01:12:58.310
And the orange-y/brown-y color is
where we still have to do a bit

01:12:58.310 --> 01:13:01.350
of work on this where
the status is unclear.

01:13:01.350 --> 01:13:04.170
Now before you all jump all
over me and say, "Oh, no.

01:13:04.170 --> 01:13:05.470
I disagree with this.

01:13:05.470 --> 01:13:07.380
I disagree with that
one," let me say

01:13:07.380 --> 01:13:10.080
that these countries have
self-identified these.

01:13:10.080 --> 01:13:11.820
This is not something
that we have imposed.

01:13:11.820 --> 01:13:13.500
They have said, "Yes,
we have a board," or,

01:13:13.500 --> 01:13:14.800
"No, we don't have a board."

01:13:14.800 --> 01:13:17.730
And of course, you can see from
the date at the top this is sort

01:13:17.730 --> 01:13:20.360
of ongoing and changeable.

01:13:20.360 --> 01:13:23.860
And I could point out that
the number of countries

01:13:23.860 --> 01:13:28.690
in Africa grew considerably in the
'60s when they gained independence

01:13:28.690 --> 01:13:30.790
and set up their names authorities.

01:13:30.790 --> 01:13:34.950
And then similarly, in countries
that came from the breakup

01:13:34.950 --> 01:13:39.290
of the Soviet Union or from breakup
of Yugoslavia were quite quick

01:13:39.290 --> 01:13:41.480
to establish names authorities.

01:13:41.480 --> 01:13:45.720
For those countries that
don't have authorities,

01:13:45.720 --> 01:13:47.860 position:56%
this can be quite a hard sell for us

01:13:47.860 --> 01:13:50.550
to convince them that
it would be useful.

01:13:50.550 --> 01:13:56.850 position:56%
Of course, we can't compete with
water and health, nor can we compete

01:13:56.850 --> 01:14:01.220
with trying to have accommodation
of some sort, living facilities,

01:14:01.220 --> 01:14:07.850 position:56%
or with education, with food supply,
or with transportation routes.

01:14:07.850 --> 01:14:13.940
But basic to all those
agencies is the use

01:14:13.940 --> 01:14:17.550
of standardized geographical names,
even if it's under the surface

01:14:17.550 --> 01:14:20.280
and not clearly recognized.

01:14:20.280 --> 01:14:23.530
So we can talk about the
benefits of standardized names,

01:14:23.530 --> 01:14:25.990
and we can do this on a
sort of overlapping basis.

01:14:25.990 --> 01:14:28.400
This is just in general terms.

01:14:28.400 --> 01:14:31.110
We might talk about technical
benefits, for instance,

01:14:31.110 --> 01:14:34.860
in different forms of mapping
and information management;

01:14:34.860 --> 01:14:38.800
of economic benefits for
clear delivery services

01:14:38.800 --> 01:14:43.140
and promoting your tourism it's
better not to have ambiguity.

01:14:43.140 --> 01:14:46.940 position:56%
If we're talking about social
benefits you've got humanitarian aid

01:14:46.940 --> 01:14:49.650
and search and rescue where
you certainly don't want many

01:14:49.650 --> 01:14:51.270
different names.

01:14:51.270 --> 01:14:54.290
And we can talk about
cultural benefits and the idea

01:14:54.290 --> 01:14:55.800
of retaining your language,

01:14:55.800 --> 01:15:01.470
or in terms of identity
ambiguity is not very helpful.

01:15:01.470 --> 01:15:04.810
Some examples of lack
of standardized data

01:15:04.810 --> 01:15:12.510
or standardized names, in Pakistan
-- this was back in 2005 --

01:15:12.510 --> 01:15:17.580
the United Nations Office for
Humanitarian Affairs was dealing

01:15:17.580 --> 01:15:21.230
with rescue operations
or aid operations

01:15:21.230 --> 01:15:24.770
after the earthquake
up in the mountains.

01:15:24.770 --> 01:15:27.800
And there were all sorts of
delays in providing assistance

01:15:27.800 --> 01:15:30.080
to these remote villages partly

01:15:30.080 --> 01:15:33.660
because they could not
obtain standardized names.

01:15:33.660 --> 01:15:36.660
The coordinates weren't
available for the villages.

01:15:36.660 --> 01:15:40.030
There were no gazetteers
to be handed out.

01:15:40.030 --> 01:15:42.020
They didn't know the
population statistics.

01:15:42.020 --> 01:15:45.630
And they didn't have maps
So all this, of course,

01:15:45.630 --> 01:15:50.930
contributes to thousands of people
who lost their lives as a result

01:15:50.930 --> 01:15:53.960
of this earthquake and aid
not reaching them quickly.

01:15:53.960 --> 01:15:59.330
By contrast, a year or so later
Indonesia had similar problems,

01:15:59.330 --> 01:16:02.030
but their data was
in much better shape

01:16:02.030 --> 01:16:07.630
and was much more helpful
to those providing aid.

01:16:07.630 --> 01:16:10.060
A similar one, this is in Somalia,

01:16:10.060 --> 01:16:14.780
and this is the United Nations
Economic Commission for Africa.

01:16:14.780 --> 01:16:19.360
And you can see on the list here
they are providing different forms

01:16:19.360 --> 01:16:21.940
for the names in Roman alphabet.

01:16:21.940 --> 01:16:28.170
And they found that duplication of
names, repetition, obviously lack

01:16:28.170 --> 01:16:32.160
of standardization, and the
data not even being available

01:16:32.160 --> 01:16:36.070
for some areas had a lot
of significance to them.

01:16:36.070 --> 01:16:37.860
They lost resources.

01:16:37.860 --> 01:16:40.380
Security could be compromised
over this.

01:16:40.380 --> 01:16:44.380
There certainly was confusion with
these multiple spellings of names.

01:16:44.380 --> 01:16:48.050
And this also led to
bad decision-making.

01:16:48.050 --> 01:16:50.030
So this is some of the difficulties

01:16:50.030 --> 01:16:53.010
when you don't have
standardized names available.

01:16:53.010 --> 01:16:55.290
So I think we're clear
that we still need

01:16:55.290 --> 01:17:01.010
to encourage national names
authorities, and we also know well

01:17:01.010 --> 01:17:03.440
that crises don't stop
at national borders.

01:17:03.440 --> 01:17:07.680
So we do need to have cooperation
between countries for databases

01:17:07.680 --> 01:17:11.940
and for making information
available.

01:17:11.940 --> 01:17:15.420
I just want to look at other
international organizations.

01:17:15.420 --> 01:17:17.580 position:56%
And I still have a few minutes here.

01:17:17.580 --> 01:17:20.150
The International Hydrographic
Organization --

01:17:20.150 --> 01:17:23.390
I know there are people
here involved with that --

01:17:23.390 --> 01:17:28.060
it is a coordinating body
for hydrographic agencies

01:17:28.060 --> 01:17:30.140
and for the work that they do.

01:17:30.140 --> 01:17:33.550
It is not a decision-making
body in the terms of names

01:17:33.550 --> 01:17:36.940
of oceans and water features.

01:17:36.940 --> 01:17:40.250
Although, obviously through
"Limits of Oceans and Seas,"

01:17:40.250 --> 01:17:45.320 position:56%
one of their prominent publications,
they do have an influence.

01:17:45.320 --> 01:17:47.130
And that, as you know,
they're still trying

01:17:47.130 --> 01:17:50.920 position:56%
to be updated from the 1953 edition.

01:17:50.920 --> 01:17:56.430
The Subcommittee on Undersea
Feature Names relating

01:17:56.430 --> 01:18:02.420
to IHO does have decision-making
authority, and meets once a year,

01:18:02.420 --> 01:18:06.470 position:56%
and decides on the names of undersea
features that have been submitted

01:18:06.470 --> 01:18:12.210
to it, and keep an online gazetteer
which everybody can access.

01:18:12.210 --> 01:18:14.190
Another international group --

01:18:14.190 --> 01:18:17.340
which I cut the slide because I
thought I wouldn't have enough time

01:18:17.340 --> 01:18:21.150
-- is the Scientific Committee
for Antarctic Research.

01:18:21.150 --> 01:18:25.040
They are a gathering group rather
than a decision-making group.

01:18:25.040 --> 01:18:29.490
And I know they have
something like 39,000 names

01:18:29.490 --> 01:18:33.390
for some 17,000 features
because they gather the material

01:18:33.390 --> 01:18:34.780
from the different countries.

01:18:34.780 --> 01:18:38.400
And I believe the U.S. have
contributed something like 1/3

01:18:38.400 --> 01:18:41.560
of the names that are
in that database.

01:18:41.560 --> 01:18:46.270
And then we -- lastly, we go
beyond Earth and out into space

01:18:46.270 --> 01:18:52.130 position:56%
to the International Astronomical
Union and one of its working groups.

01:18:52.130 --> 01:18:56.080
The IAU has been in
effect since 1919.

01:18:56.080 --> 01:19:04.230 position:56%
And I think particularly with
Sputnik in 1957 and man on the moon,

01:19:04.230 --> 01:19:06.110
if you like, in the late '60s,

01:19:06.110 --> 01:19:12.330
there was much more general public
interest in features on planets,

01:19:12.330 --> 01:19:16.730
on moons, names outside Earth.

01:19:16.730 --> 01:19:20.570
In other words, toponyms
rather than geographic names.

01:19:20.570 --> 01:19:22.520
And they set up the Working Group

01:19:22.520 --> 01:19:27.160
on Planetary System
Nomenclature in 1973.

01:19:27.160 --> 01:19:33.740
Now themes have been established
for naming with this working group.

01:19:33.740 --> 01:19:38.680
And just quite recently there were
some craters named on Mercury --

01:19:38.680 --> 01:19:40.130
this was earlier this year --

01:19:40.130 --> 01:19:43.510
and they have a theme of
artists, composers, and writers.

01:19:43.510 --> 01:19:47.430 position:56%
And I was quite interested to see
that a famous Canadian photographer,

01:19:47.430 --> 01:19:55.130
Karsh, in fact, was put forward
and now has a crater named for him.

01:19:55.130 --> 01:20:00.040
He's not alive, so
he won't know that.

01:20:00.040 --> 01:20:03.880
So they are moving towards a
public involvement in these,

01:20:03.880 --> 01:20:08.180
either by contest, which that
one was, and chosen by the IAU

01:20:08.180 --> 01:20:14.000 position:56%
and this working group, or as we saw
just recently, planets associated

01:20:14.000 --> 01:20:17.410
with other stars and how
they're now having public input

01:20:17.410 --> 01:20:21.000
and public voting in fact, more
crowdsourcing of information.

01:20:24.650 --> 01:20:28.220
Right. So just to finish
off, I would like to say

01:20:28.220 --> 01:20:33.460
that I'm sure we certainly have
continued need for standardization

01:20:33.460 --> 01:20:37.090
of geographic names
to protect heritage,

01:20:37.090 --> 01:20:40.840
to integrate with other
place related data.

01:20:40.840 --> 01:20:44.110
As you've already heard,
the geographic name is one

01:20:44.110 --> 01:20:50.600 position:56%
of the main aspects that the general
public will use to query databases,

01:20:50.600 --> 01:20:54.990
so it's an important entry
point for place-related data

01:20:54.990 --> 01:20:57.250
and for linking them together.

01:20:57.250 --> 01:21:00.380
There's still a need for
accurate and up-to-date records.

01:21:00.380 --> 01:21:02.800
It's greater than ever.

01:21:02.800 --> 01:21:04.270
Although it may be challenging

01:21:04.270 --> 01:21:10.530
to name authorities today I think
we have to keep up with life,

01:21:10.530 --> 01:21:15.230
we have to grasp the opportunities
of today's communication,

01:21:15.230 --> 01:21:18.750
and this probably means
going to crowdsourcing,

01:21:18.750 --> 01:21:21.860
which I know for a name's
board is quite controversial,

01:21:21.860 --> 01:21:24.020
but I think we'll hear
about that this afternoon.

01:21:24.020 --> 01:21:25.820
So, thank you very much.

01:21:25.820 --> 01:21:39.680
[ Applause ]

