01:52:36.670 --> 01:52:40.110
I guess the -- that was we're
going to the Klondike and --

01:52:40.110 --> 01:52:45.410
Marcus Baker in his introduction
to the <i>Geographic Dictionary</i>

01:52:45.410 --> 01:52:49.090
<i>of Alaska </i>, he made the statement
that the Director of the USGS came

01:52:49.090 --> 01:52:54.540
to him at the time and said we need
to get the <i>Alaska Dictionary </i>going

01:52:54.540 --> 01:52:57.850
because we need this for
our work now at this time.

01:52:57.850 --> 01:52:59.150
It had been put on the back burner

01:52:59.150 --> 01:53:04.200
for a bit following the initial
meetings of the USBGN but because

01:53:04.200 --> 01:53:06.750
of the gold rush and
the influx of people,

01:53:06.750 --> 01:53:09.780
I'm sure that was the
driving force, ultimately,

01:53:09.780 --> 01:53:13.130
behind finishing the <i>Dictionary
of Alaska Place Names </i>.

01:53:13.130 --> 01:53:18.700
Don Orth may have a
different view on that, maybe.

01:53:18.700 --> 01:53:20.330
Okay. You're good with it.

01:53:20.330 --> 01:53:23.850
Okay. Any further questions?

01:53:23.850 --> 01:53:25.370
Okay. Thank you.

01:53:25.370 --> 01:53:27.580
[ Applause ]

01:53:27.580 --> 01:53:28.880
&gt;&gt; Douglas Caldwell: Okay.

01:53:28.880 --> 01:53:30.180
Our next speaker.

01:53:30.180 --> 01:53:33.250
We're very fortunate to have Miss
Sandra Shaw here with us today.

01:53:33.250 --> 01:53:36.200
She worked at the CIA and
the Department of State,

01:53:36.200 --> 01:53:40.240
and was the first woman
to chair the BGN.

01:53:40.240 --> 01:53:43.430
Among the assignments during her
distinguished 31-year Federal

01:53:43.430 --> 01:53:46.210
career, she served in
the Department of State

01:53:46.210 --> 01:53:48.800
as the Deputy Executive
Director of the Bureau

01:53:48.800 --> 01:53:51.420
of Intelligence and Research.

01:53:51.420 --> 01:53:54.560
She was also the Chief of
Cartography in the Office

01:53:54.560 --> 01:53:58.480
of the Geographer where she
oversaw cartographic support

01:53:58.480 --> 01:54:02.280
for key diplomatic initiatives.

01:54:02.280 --> 01:54:04.550 position:56%
Given her experience with all facets

01:54:04.550 --> 01:54:08.190
of the BGN she is exceptionally
well-qualified

01:54:08.190 --> 01:54:12.540
to help us better understand
how the Board has evolved.

01:54:12.540 --> 01:54:14.340
Sandra.

01:54:14.340 --> 01:54:24.070
[ Applause ]

01:54:24.070 --> 01:54:26.340 position:56%
&gt;&gt; Sandra Shaw: Thank you very much.

01:54:26.340 --> 01:54:29.870
I'd like to thank the U.S. Board in
Geographic Names and its Chairman,

01:54:29.870 --> 01:54:32.790
Douglas Caldwell, for inviting
me to participate today

01:54:32.790 --> 01:54:36.820 position:56%
in this 125th anniversary symposium.

01:54:36.820 --> 01:54:40.240
It's an honor and a pleasure
to be here, to be re-acquainted

01:54:40.240 --> 01:54:43.800
with former BGN colleagues,
and to meet current members

01:54:43.800 --> 01:54:46.580
and the many distinguished
participants and guest

01:54:46.580 --> 01:54:48.520 position:56%
who have gathered today to recognize

01:54:48.520 --> 01:54:52.370
and honor the extraordinary
work of the BGN.

01:54:52.370 --> 01:54:55.630
Captain Theberge has presented you
with a fascinating introduction

01:54:55.630 --> 01:54:56.930
to the origins of the BGN.

01:54:56.930 --> 01:55:01.260
Its evolution's been a
journey down a long, winding,

01:55:01.260 --> 01:55:06.950
and sometimes weary road from its
creation in 1890 to its expansion

01:55:06.950 --> 01:55:13.120 position:56%
of authority in 1906, its
abolishment as an independent agency

01:55:13.120 --> 01:55:19.670
in 1934, the granting of its
statuatory authority in 1947,

01:55:19.670 --> 01:55:22.550
and the eventual transfer
of the domestic names

01:55:22.550 --> 01:55:25.090
to the Geological Survey,

01:55:25.090 --> 01:55:27.910
and the foreign names
to the Army Map Service.

01:55:27.910 --> 01:55:32.930
The BGN has endured the 125-year
journey through the dedication

01:55:32.930 --> 01:55:35.210
and innovation of its
members in support

01:55:35.210 --> 01:55:37.770
of their respective organizations.

01:55:37.770 --> 01:55:41.200
Sixteen years after
its establishment,

01:55:41.200 --> 01:55:45.480
President Theodore Roosevelt issued
an Executive Order which added

01:55:45.480 --> 01:55:50.290 position:56%
to the BGN "the duty of determining,
changing, and fixing place names

01:55:50.290 --> 01:55:53.950
within the United States
and insular possessions.

01:55:53.950 --> 01:55:57.350
All names suggested for
any place by any officer

01:55:57.350 --> 01:56:01.850
of the government shall be referred
to the Board for consideration

01:56:01.850 --> 01:56:05.530
and approval before publication."

01:56:05.530 --> 01:56:10.960
A second Order was issued in August
10th changing the official title

01:56:10.960 --> 01:56:13.740
of the United States
Board in Geographic Names

01:56:13.740 --> 01:56:16.860
to the United States
Geographic Board,

01:56:16.860 --> 01:56:20.440
and granting it advisory powers
concerning the preparation

01:56:20.440 --> 01:56:24.730
of maps compiled in the government
to avoid unnecessary duplication

01:56:24.730 --> 01:56:30.440
of work and to unify and
improve map scales and symbols.

01:56:30.440 --> 01:56:33.140
The Board would only
hold the advisory powers

01:56:33.140 --> 01:56:37.300
for 13 years before they
were transferred in 1919

01:56:37.300 --> 01:56:41.260
to the newly established
Board of Surveys and Maps.

01:56:41.260 --> 01:56:45.280
The new authorities
presented the Geographic Board

01:56:45.280 --> 01:56:47.350
with a formidable task.

01:56:47.350 --> 01:56:51.340
With only 13 Board Members, most
of whom held senior positions

01:56:51.340 --> 01:56:55.190
in their respective
departments, no staff support,

01:56:55.190 --> 01:57:00.170
and an edict that the Board and
its work would entail no expense

01:57:00.170 --> 01:57:02.470
on the government [laughter].

01:57:04.200 --> 01:57:07.630
Lack of staff and funding would
persist throughout the history

01:57:07.630 --> 01:57:13.360
of the BGN, even after it gained
statuatory authority in 1947.

01:57:13.360 --> 01:57:16.010
In my discussion of
this period of 1906

01:57:16.010 --> 01:57:19.890
through 1934 the Geographic
Board will simply be referred

01:57:19.890 --> 01:57:21.190
to as the Board.

01:57:24.110 --> 01:57:25.800
The records did not reveal why

01:57:25.800 --> 01:57:28.370
or by whom these new
authorities were proposed,

01:57:28.370 --> 01:57:31.500
but it seems reasonable that
the Board itself sought broader

01:57:31.500 --> 01:57:36.350
authority to maintain uniform
usage of names in the government.

01:57:36.350 --> 01:57:40.700 position:56%
Additionally, many Board Members
were involved in mapping activities,

01:57:40.700 --> 01:57:44.500
including its Chairman, Henry
Gannett, Chief Geographer

01:57:44.500 --> 01:57:48.420
of the Geological Survey, who is
often considered to be the father

01:57:48.420 --> 01:57:51.600
of topographic mapping
in the United States.

01:57:51.600 --> 01:57:56.760
Henry Gannett chaired the
Board until his death in 1914.

01:57:56.760 --> 01:57:58.620
On his deathbed, he was informed

01:57:58.620 --> 01:58:02.930 position:56%
that he had again been elected
Chairman, and he replied [laughter],

01:58:02.930 --> 01:58:08.660
"You were determined I shall
die in the harness, and I will."

01:58:08.660 --> 01:58:13.280
The last of the original
BGN members,

01:58:13.280 --> 01:58:17.380
Mr. Gannett was also a founder of
the National Geographic Society

01:58:17.380 --> 01:58:22.610
and concurrently served as its
President from 1910 to 1914.

01:58:22.610 --> 01:58:24.140
You'll hear more about the BGN

01:58:24.140 --> 01:58:27.920
and the National Geographic
this afternoon from Mr. Valdez.

01:58:27.920 --> 01:58:32.000
Following the 1906 actions,
the Board moved quickly

01:58:32.000 --> 01:58:35.090 position:56%
to develop principles for new names.

01:58:35.090 --> 01:58:37.870
It streamlined the
names approval process

01:58:37.870 --> 01:58:41.900
and addressed the advisory
powers, establishing a committee

01:58:41.900 --> 01:58:44.700
to standardize map symbols.

01:58:44.700 --> 01:58:50.020
By 1911, the Board published
conventional signs adopted

01:58:50.020 --> 01:58:54.360
by the United States Geographic
Board that provided a standard set

01:58:54.360 --> 01:58:57.440
of signs, symbols, and
abbreviations for use

01:58:57.440 --> 01:59:00.410
on all government maps and charts.

01:59:00.410 --> 01:59:04.390 position:56%
The work of the Board was primarily
conducted by the Executive Committee

01:59:04.390 --> 01:59:06.740
with their recommendation
of names decisions sent

01:59:06.740 --> 01:59:10.260
to the full Board before
promulgation.

01:59:10.260 --> 01:59:12.870 position:56%
However, to expedite the new duties,

01:59:12.870 --> 01:59:21.210
the Executive Committee's
authority was expanded to approve

01:59:21.210 --> 01:59:25.310 position:56%
or reject all new names submitted by
the Geological Survey and the Coast

01:59:25.310 --> 01:59:29.810
and Geodetic Survey without
waiting for Board approval.

01:59:29.810 --> 01:59:32.110
The Chairman was to act
on behalf of the Board

01:59:32.110 --> 01:59:35.700
in all names submitted
by the Post Office.

01:59:35.700 --> 01:59:39.080
Postal names had been confusing
and an issue from early

01:59:39.080 --> 01:59:41.700
in the Board's history,
with many instances

01:59:41.700 --> 01:59:45.000
of the Post Office and
town name differing.

01:59:45.000 --> 01:59:49.780
There was a new urgency in the
approval process since between 30

01:59:49.780 --> 01:59:54.920
and 40 postal names
were established daily.

01:59:54.920 --> 02:00:00.450
Between 1906 and 1934, the
U.S. would enter World War I

02:00:00.450 --> 02:00:02.280
and suffer the Great Depression.

02:00:02.280 --> 02:00:07.220 position:56%
But through these events the Board
made progress, no matter how slowly.

02:00:07.220 --> 02:00:11.660
World War I, unlike World War II,
did not require mass production

02:00:11.660 --> 02:00:17.110
of foreign names and had minimal
effect on the work of the Board.

02:00:17.110 --> 02:00:19.430
If anything, it slowed
the work since many

02:00:19.430 --> 02:00:22.760
of the members were
away at war duty.

02:00:22.760 --> 02:00:25.150 position:56%
This was a period of Board outreach.

02:00:25.150 --> 02:00:28.980
It established an Advisory
Board of outside specialists,

02:00:28.980 --> 02:00:32.150
enlisted the assistance of
state names authorities,

02:00:32.150 --> 02:00:36.760 position:56%
and encouraged establishment of
such authorities where none existed.

02:00:36.760 --> 02:00:39.730
It strengthened and developed
international collaborative efforts

02:00:39.730 --> 02:00:42.790
with names authorities such as
the Geographic Board of Canada,

02:00:42.790 --> 02:00:46.400
the Royal Geographical Society,
and the Permanent Committee

02:00:46.400 --> 02:00:49.890
on Geographic Names for
Official British Use,

02:00:49.890 --> 02:00:55.800
and also increased the focus
on foreign geographic names.

02:00:57.250 --> 02:01:00.150
Also, after 30 years of
requests for funding,

02:01:00.150 --> 02:01:05.520
the Board received its first direct
appropriations from Congress.

02:01:05.520 --> 02:01:10.100
Starting in 1920 and continuing
until it was abolished in 1934

02:01:10.100 --> 02:01:14.680
as an independent board,
it received about $79,000

02:01:14.680 --> 02:01:16.860
in direct appropriations.

02:01:16.860 --> 02:01:22.600
That would approximate about
1.2 million in 2015 dollars.

02:01:22.600 --> 02:01:27.690
The funding peaked in 1934
which reflected the salaries

02:01:27.690 --> 02:01:31.330
of the Chairman, the
Secretary, and Assistant Clerk,

02:01:31.330 --> 02:01:36.130
all devoting full time
to the work of the Board.

02:01:36.130 --> 02:01:40.370
Another Board first would come
in 1925 when the first woman,

02:01:40.370 --> 02:01:43.440
Dr. Helen Strong, was
appointed to the Board

02:01:43.440 --> 02:01:46.030
by the Department of Commerce.

02:01:46.030 --> 02:01:47.950
She had prepared a
Congressional study

02:01:47.950 --> 02:01:51.540
on U.S. foreign agricultural trade
that garnered her the position

02:01:51.540 --> 02:01:56.450
of Geographer of the Bureau of
Foreign and Domestic Commerce.

02:01:56.450 --> 02:01:59.860
During her nine-year tenure on the
Board she would be instrumental

02:01:59.860 --> 02:02:04.080
in the Board's work on
foreign geographic names.

02:02:04.080 --> 02:02:11.020
Dr. Strong is seated in the lower
right of the 1932 Board photo.

02:02:12.130 --> 02:02:15.620
Since World War I there had been
a growing need for decisions

02:02:15.620 --> 02:02:17.680
on foreign names within
the government,

02:02:17.680 --> 02:02:19.410
as well as the private sector.

02:02:19.410 --> 02:02:24.850
In 1926, Board Chairman, Frank
Bond, appointed a committee

02:02:24.850 --> 02:02:28.490
to consider the entire
subject of foreign names.

02:02:28.490 --> 02:02:32.060
The final work of the Committee,
composed of Dr. Samuel Boggs

02:02:32.060 --> 02:02:37.730
of the State Department and Dr.
Helen Strong, was published in 1932

02:02:37.730 --> 02:02:42.090
as the Board's "First Report
on Foreign Geographic Names."

02:02:42.090 --> 02:02:47.730 position:56%
It was a tutorial on the treatment
of foreign names addressing policies

02:02:47.730 --> 02:02:52.240
and procedures, guides for
transliteration, pronunciation,

02:02:52.240 --> 02:02:57.260
abbreviation, and even gave tips
on proper business protocol,

02:02:57.260 --> 02:03:02.440
as well as a list of 2500
foreign names decisions.

02:03:02.440 --> 02:03:06.000
The report gained press
coverage, even a quarter column

02:03:06.000 --> 02:03:09.900
in the <i>New York Times</i>
titled, "Foreign Place Names."

02:03:09.900 --> 02:03:13.350
The reporter observed, "One of
the evidences that we've come

02:03:13.350 --> 02:03:17.430
into a consolidated world is a
United States Government report

02:03:17.430 --> 02:03:20.950
about the spelling of
foreign geographic names.

02:03:20.950 --> 02:03:24.030
If only there had been
added another hundred pages

02:03:24.030 --> 02:03:29.270
by some Homeric Earth wanderer who
had seen the cities of many men

02:03:29.270 --> 02:03:34.540
and learned their manners, it might
easily be the book of the month."

02:03:34.540 --> 02:03:37.640 position:56%
Though the report was well-received,

02:03:37.640 --> 02:03:41.450
the Board conducted practically
no other work on foreign names

02:03:41.450 --> 02:03:44.740
until it was faced with
the monumental task

02:03:44.740 --> 02:03:49.550
of standardizing millions of
names in support of World War II.

02:03:51.390 --> 02:03:55.800
I call 1934 "The Board's Waterloo."

02:03:55.800 --> 02:04:01.260 position:56%
April 17th, Franklin Roosevelt
signed an Executive Order abolishing

02:04:01.260 --> 02:04:05.060
the United States Geographic
Board and transferring all

02:04:05.060 --> 02:04:09.340
of its functions to the
Department of Interior.

02:04:09.340 --> 02:04:12.250
The Executive Order attributes
the President's actions

02:04:12.250 --> 02:04:17.270
to the 1933 Reorganization Act, but
there also seems to be a back story

02:04:17.270 --> 02:04:19.480
to the President's actions.

02:04:19.480 --> 02:04:22.480
It involves his Secretary
of Interior,

02:04:22.480 --> 02:04:25.390
Harold Ickes, and Hoover Dam.

02:04:25.390 --> 02:04:31.850
At inception, the Dam Project
was simply known as Boulder Dam.

02:04:31.850 --> 02:04:35.040
But at the ceremony to start
the project Hoover's Secretary

02:04:35.040 --> 02:04:39.070
of Interior, Ray Lyman Wilbur,
announced, "I have the honor

02:04:39.070 --> 02:04:42.550
and privilege of giving a
name to this new structure.

02:04:42.550 --> 02:04:45.670
It shall be called Hoover Dam."

02:04:45.670 --> 02:04:51.030
When Roosevelt took office in
1933, his Secretary of Interior,

02:04:51.030 --> 02:04:55.510
Harold Ickes, changed the name to
Boulder Dam, justifying his action

02:04:55.510 --> 02:05:01.020
by saying, "The men who pioneered
this project knew it by this name."

02:05:01.020 --> 02:05:04.420
Ickes' action was not without
critics, some writing directly

02:05:04.420 --> 02:05:08.400
to him and others to
the Geographic Board.

02:05:08.400 --> 02:05:10.730
It seems Secretary
Ickes was not pleased

02:05:10.730 --> 02:05:12.490
that a Federal Authority existed

02:05:12.490 --> 02:05:14.480
that could overturn
his naming action,

02:05:14.480 --> 02:05:20.220 position:56%
so in 1934 Ickes drafted the
Executive Order to abolish the Board

02:05:20.220 --> 02:05:23.670
for Roosevelt's consideration.

02:05:23.670 --> 02:05:24.970
The Director of the Bureau

02:05:24.970 --> 02:05:28.250
of the Budget advised
Roosevelt against such action.

02:05:28.250 --> 02:05:31.630 position:56%
However, he did not heed his advice.

02:05:32.700 --> 02:05:36.410 position:56%
It created concern about many in the
government as well as in the private

02:05:36.410 --> 02:05:40.240
and scientific community,
including Dr. Isaiah Bowman,

02:05:40.240 --> 02:05:44.200
a member of President
Roosevelt's Science Advisory Board

02:05:44.200 --> 02:05:48.100
and Former President of the
American Geographical Society.

02:05:48.100 --> 02:05:53.370 position:56%
He wrote to the Secretary indicating
he had read about the abolishment

02:05:53.370 --> 02:05:56.470
of the Board and hoped
that "If it is discontinued

02:05:56.470 --> 02:05:59.830
under its present name its
functions will be carried

02:05:59.830 --> 02:06:02.630
on as effectively as in the past.

02:06:02.630 --> 02:06:05.840
It is of great importance
from every standpoint

02:06:05.840 --> 02:06:09.420
that such an organization
should exist in the government.

02:06:09.420 --> 02:06:12.280
Under no circumstances
should this work be assumed

02:06:12.280 --> 02:06:14.710
by an outside agency.

02:06:14.710 --> 02:06:18.150
It would be a relatively simple
matter to set up an adequate Board

02:06:18.150 --> 02:06:20.560
in the Department of Interior."

02:06:20.560 --> 02:06:26.800 position:56%
Bowman closed his letter by offering
his services to discuss such a plan.

02:06:26.800 --> 02:06:30.500
Secretary Ickes actually may be
credited rather than vilified

02:06:30.500 --> 02:06:34.670
for providing a home in which the
Board could more easily structure

02:06:34.670 --> 02:06:38.720
and ramp up its work to effectively
support the upcoming requirements

02:06:38.720 --> 02:06:40.880
of World War II.

02:06:40.880 --> 02:06:45.760
Also, if the Board had
maintained its independent status,

02:06:45.760 --> 02:06:48.010
would Dr. Meredith Peat
Furrell [assumed spelling],

02:06:48.010 --> 02:06:52.280
a Geographer in the Department
of Interior, be in the history

02:06:52.280 --> 02:06:55.960 position:56%
of the BGN or International
Standardization of Geographic Names?

02:06:55.960 --> 02:07:00.300
Following the transfer the
Secretary established the Division

02:07:00.300 --> 02:07:04.510
of Geographic Names and an Advisory
Committee on Geographic Names

02:07:04.510 --> 02:07:06.760
which has centrally
mirrored the membership

02:07:06.760 --> 02:07:09.180
of the abolished Geographic Board,

02:07:09.180 --> 02:07:12.170
but also included individuals
representing a number

02:07:12.170 --> 02:07:14.950
of geographical societies.

02:07:14.950 --> 02:07:19.690
He appointed Walter Mendenhall,
Director of the Geological Survey

02:07:19.690 --> 02:07:23.370
and nephew of BGN Founder,
Thomas Mendenhall,

02:07:23.370 --> 02:07:26.750
as the Executive Officer
of the Division.

02:07:26.750 --> 02:07:29.150
Shortly afterward,
Mendenhall recommended

02:07:29.150 --> 02:07:32.670
that an authoritative name
for the two units was needed

02:07:32.670 --> 02:07:36.030
for publication of names decisions.

02:07:36.030 --> 02:07:38.450
At first, Secretary
Ickes was not receptive

02:07:38.450 --> 02:07:43.690
to essentially reestablishing the
BGN, but reconsidered upon advice

02:07:43.690 --> 02:07:48.090
of Dr. Bowman, and issued a
departmental order explaining

02:07:48.090 --> 02:07:50.170
that for simplicity of reference,

02:07:50.170 --> 02:07:54.500
these two units together will be
designated United States Board

02:07:54.500 --> 02:07:57.410
on Geographical Names.

02:07:57.410 --> 02:08:02.120 position:56%
At the first meeting of the Advisory
Committee, Secretary Ickes said he

02:08:02.120 --> 02:08:05.620
and the President were both
opposed to naming place

02:08:05.620 --> 02:08:10.630
after living persons, and that he
had more than once been shocked

02:08:10.630 --> 02:08:14.410
by the names selected for
some of our natural objects.

02:08:14.410 --> 02:08:17.070
Names of people that the
American people would

02:08:17.070 --> 02:08:22.060
like to forget have been affixed
to the objects that were inanimate

02:08:22.060 --> 02:08:24.260
and thus unable to
protest [laughter].

02:08:24.260 --> 02:08:29.080
"I hope that this Committee will
adopt a policy of not yielding

02:08:29.080 --> 02:08:32.450
to political pressure in
such an important matter

02:08:32.450 --> 02:08:35.760
as the selection of a name."

02:08:35.760 --> 02:08:39.250
Until World War II, the work
of the BGN was conducted

02:08:39.250 --> 02:08:40.550
by the Executive Committee

02:08:40.550 --> 02:08:44.210
and the full Board met
only about once a year.

02:08:44.210 --> 02:08:48.210
In 1941, the BGN broadened
its responsibilities

02:08:48.210 --> 02:08:51.050
to include the standardization
of traditionally

02:08:51.050 --> 02:08:55.210
or newly named undersea features,
which led to the establishment

02:08:55.210 --> 02:09:00.470
of the Advisory Committee in
Undersea Features in 1963.

02:09:00.470 --> 02:09:04.870
With 3- to 400 domestic names
decisions published yearly,

02:09:04.870 --> 02:09:08.640
the BGN did practically
no work on foreign names.

02:09:08.640 --> 02:09:10.850
Upcoming American military

02:09:10.850 --> 02:09:15.120
and intelligence requirements
brought sweeping change to its work

02:09:15.120 --> 02:09:20.740
and would be the coming of age of
BGN's foreign names activities.

02:09:20.740 --> 02:09:24.410
With the U.S. Declaration of
War, the BGN entered a new era

02:09:24.410 --> 02:09:28.360
of production that no
longer allowed the luxury

02:09:28.360 --> 02:09:30.730
of approving individual names.

02:09:30.730 --> 02:09:34.720
For the first time, the Board
had ample staff and funds

02:09:34.720 --> 02:09:40.530
to support its work, or at
least its work on foreign names.

02:09:40.530 --> 02:09:43.720
Through an agreement between the
Interior and the War Department,

02:09:43.720 --> 02:09:47.540
approved by the President, the
War Department transferred funds

02:09:47.540 --> 02:09:52.470
to reimburse Interior for the
BGN foreign names activities.

02:09:52.470 --> 02:09:59.670 position:56%
As you can see, the funding peaked
in 1944 which came to about $400,000

02:09:59.670 --> 02:10:02.740
that they were transferring
into Interior

02:10:02.740 --> 02:10:05.970
for the Board's work
on foreign names only.

02:10:07.410 --> 02:10:11.710
Secretary Ickes selected
Dr. Meredith Burrill,

02:10:11.710 --> 02:10:17.800
a Geographer serving as the
Chief of Analysts and Research

02:10:17.800 --> 02:10:22.590
in the General Land Office, to lead
the reorganization of the Board.

02:10:22.590 --> 02:10:27.700
In a 1967 interview, Dr.
Burrill indicated that he was

02:10:27.700 --> 02:10:30.600
about the only Geographer around,

02:10:30.600 --> 02:10:32.990
"so the Secretary of
Interior picked me."

02:10:32.990 --> 02:10:39.320
By the end of 1943, the Division
had increased from a pre-war staff

02:10:39.320 --> 02:10:45.610 position:56%
of two to of about 180, which
included geographers, cartographers,

02:10:45.610 --> 02:10:50.130
linguists, historians,
librarians, and clerks.

02:10:50.130 --> 02:10:51.850
In the words of Dr. Burrill,

02:10:51.850 --> 02:10:55.080
"The task of making ready
these geographical tools

02:10:55.080 --> 02:11:00.830
of war was not unlike that faced
by the manufacturer of airplanes."

02:11:00.830 --> 02:11:04.470 position:56%
The goal that had to be attained
would have been considered fantastic

02:11:04.470 --> 02:11:07.310
before the war.

02:11:07.310 --> 02:11:11.050 position:56%
The name of the Division was changed
to the Division of Geography,

02:11:11.050 --> 02:11:12.620
and the work of the Division staff

02:11:12.620 --> 02:11:16.080
and Advisory Committee
was redefined.

02:11:16.080 --> 02:11:18.960
To expedite work, the
Secretary delegated

02:11:18.960 --> 02:11:20.790
to Dr. Burrill the authority

02:11:20.790 --> 02:11:25.960
to approve all domestic names
conforming to existing procedures,

02:11:25.960 --> 02:11:29.760
and all foreign names
either derived by approved

02:11:29.760 --> 02:11:32.410
or unapproved procedures.

02:11:32.410 --> 02:11:34.930
The Division took on
the responsibility

02:11:34.930 --> 02:11:38.120
of establishing major rules
and policies for the treatment

02:11:38.120 --> 02:11:41.730
of both domestic and
foreign names, investigating

02:11:41.730 --> 02:11:44.470
and recommending action
on names issues,

02:11:44.470 --> 02:11:49.300
while the Advisory Committee simply
reviewed principles, policies,

02:11:49.300 --> 02:11:53.970
and name recommendations prior
to approval by the Secretary.

02:11:53.970 --> 02:11:58.990
A special Committee on
Antarctic names was established

02:11:58.990 --> 02:12:03.460
that also became the
Advisory Committee in 1947.

02:12:03.460 --> 02:12:07.860
The BGN became a clearing house
for names, producing indexes

02:12:07.860 --> 02:12:12.020
for European invasion maps,
gazetteers, and the transcription

02:12:12.020 --> 02:12:16.830
of some 3 million Chinese,
Japanese, and Korean names.

02:12:17.930 --> 02:12:23.810
This is an example of a
long-range air navigation chart

02:12:23.810 --> 02:12:27.730
which is a typical
product that was produced

02:12:27.730 --> 02:12:30.260
by the BGN during that period.

02:12:30.260 --> 02:12:35.260
The Army would submit a
blue-line proof of the map,

02:12:35.260 --> 02:12:39.420
and the BGN would prepare what
they called a names overlay.

02:12:39.420 --> 02:12:43.090
All of these black areas are
names that they've gone in

02:12:43.090 --> 02:12:47.310
and applied by hand in ink.

02:12:48.930 --> 02:12:52.850 position:56%
Once they applied the names overlay,
they would return this to the Army

02:12:52.850 --> 02:12:56.110
for application and
final production.

02:12:57.270 --> 02:12:59.610
The war ended in 1945,

02:12:59.610 --> 02:13:03.060
but standardizing foreign
names was only beginning.

02:13:03.060 --> 02:13:05.700
The BGN would continue work

02:13:05.700 --> 02:13:08.500
on a reimbursable basis
producing gazetteers

02:13:08.500 --> 02:13:10.730
and other names requirements
for the military

02:13:10.730 --> 02:13:15.270
and intelligence programs
for years to come.

02:13:15.270 --> 02:13:18.870
However, Cold War funding
for foreign names that ranged

02:13:18.870 --> 02:13:24.620
from about 200,000 in
1946 to a high of 580,000

02:13:24.620 --> 02:13:29.000
in 1965 became a two-edge
sword for the BGN.

02:13:32.580 --> 02:13:37.500
In 1945 the Chairman of the House
Committee on Appropriations stated

02:13:37.500 --> 02:13:41.260
that all agencies of the
government that lacked authority

02:13:41.260 --> 02:13:45.810
for lawful appropriations
must seek legislation.

02:13:45.810 --> 02:13:48.670
The BGN took action and on July 25,

02:13:48.670 --> 02:13:54.440
1947 President Harry Truman signed
a bill establishing the U.S. Board

02:13:54.440 --> 02:13:57.000
on Geographic Names.

02:13:57.000 --> 02:14:00.670
Conjointly with the Secretary of
Interior, the BGN would "provide

02:14:00.670 --> 02:14:03.650
for uniformity and
geographic nomenclature

02:14:03.650 --> 02:14:06.590
and orthography throughout
the Federal Government"

02:14:06.590 --> 02:14:10.280
and would be authorized to
be appropriated such funds

02:14:10.280 --> 02:14:15.750
as may be necessary to carry
out the purposes of this Act.

02:14:15.750 --> 02:14:19.610
Additionally, the Act authorized
the Secretary to take action

02:14:19.610 --> 02:14:25.790 position:56%
in any matter wherein the Board does
not act within a reasonable time.

02:14:25.790 --> 02:14:29.590
This has been mentioned before,
but we saw earlier in August

02:14:29.590 --> 02:14:35.520
or late August that the
Secretary exercised that authority

02:14:35.520 --> 02:14:38.800
when she changed the name
from Mount McKinley to Denali.

02:14:38.800 --> 02:14:44.040
In my opinion, I think this
is the only time a Secretary

02:14:44.040 --> 02:14:49.690
of Interior has exercised
this authority.

02:14:49.690 --> 02:14:54.610
The BGN's first meeting under
statuatory authority was spent

02:14:54.610 --> 02:14:58.870
on organizational matters including
the establishment of committees,

02:14:58.870 --> 02:15:02.410
election of officers, and the
appointment of Dr. Burrill

02:15:02.410 --> 02:15:06.290
as the BGN Executive Secretary.

02:15:06.290 --> 02:15:10.020
However, gaining statuatory
authority did not have the results

02:15:10.020 --> 02:15:12.170
the BGN sought.

02:15:12.170 --> 02:15:15.850
Between 1947 and 1950,
the Division continued

02:15:15.850 --> 02:15:18.700
to receive small direct
appropriations for the work

02:15:18.700 --> 02:15:22.550
of the BGN, but efforts
to seek additional funds

02:15:22.550 --> 02:15:25.540
for domestic names
activities was hindered

02:15:25.540 --> 02:15:30.280
by the large sums available
for foreign names.

02:15:30.280 --> 02:15:34.660
In the early 1950s, concern grew
among the Domestic Names Committee

02:15:34.660 --> 02:15:39.600
members over the lack of adequate
funds to address its backlog.

02:15:39.600 --> 02:15:44.170
Some agencies no longer submitted
cases for staff processing.

02:15:44.170 --> 02:15:48.860
Several Interior management
reports published between 1952

02:15:48.860 --> 02:15:55.170
and 1955 indicated that the work
of the domestic names was in chaos

02:15:55.170 --> 02:15:58.800
because no funds were
available for needed work.

02:15:58.800 --> 02:16:00.540
The reports recommended options

02:16:00.540 --> 02:16:03.070
such as transferring the
domestic names activities

02:16:03.070 --> 02:16:07.910 position:56%
to the Geological Survey,
divesting the Department of the work

02:16:07.910 --> 02:16:10.490
on foreign gazetteers,

02:16:10.490 --> 02:16:14.580
and transferring the
foreign names functions

02:16:14.580 --> 02:16:18.490
to another appropriate agency.

02:16:18.490 --> 02:16:23.020
No action was taken until 1958
when the domestic names activities,

02:16:23.020 --> 02:16:26.210
including several staff
members, were transferred

02:16:26.210 --> 02:16:30.160
to the Geological Survey,
and an Executive Secretary

02:16:30.160 --> 02:16:32.760
for Domestic Names,
Jerome Kilmartin,

02:16:32.760 --> 02:16:36.630
was appointed by the
Survey to head the program.

02:16:36.630 --> 02:16:42.560
Dr. Burrill remained the Secretary
for Foreign Names and the BGN.

02:16:42.560 --> 02:16:45.780
It took until 1962 for
the domestic names staff

02:16:45.780 --> 02:16:49.980
to clear the decisions
of its backlog.

02:16:49.980 --> 02:16:54.640
In 1959, Donald Orth joined
the Domestic Names staff.

02:16:54.640 --> 02:16:59.490 position:56%
He was appointed the Executive
Secretary for Domestic Names in 1963

02:16:59.490 --> 02:17:03.510
and was a formidable leader of
the program, expanding its work

02:17:03.510 --> 02:17:08.740
and guiding it into the digital
age until his retirement in 1991.

02:17:08.740 --> 02:17:10.310
Roger Payne succeeded him

02:17:10.310 --> 02:17:14.180
as the Executive Secretary
for Domestic Names.

02:17:14.180 --> 02:17:18.530
Another 10 years elapsed before the
Foreign Names staff functions were

02:17:18.530 --> 02:17:21.030
transferred from Interior
to the Department

02:17:21.030 --> 02:17:23.630
of Defense Army Map Service.

02:17:23.630 --> 02:17:26.690
During that period, the BGN
became actively involved

02:17:26.690 --> 02:17:29.700
in international standardization
efforts.

02:17:29.700 --> 02:17:32.450 position:56%
In 1956, at the request of the U.N.,

02:17:32.450 --> 02:17:36.790
Dr. Burrill drafted a proposed
program addressing international

02:17:36.790 --> 02:17:39.690 position:56%
standardization of geographic names.

02:17:39.690 --> 02:17:43.000
His work was instrumental
in the U.N.'s development

02:17:43.000 --> 02:17:47.530
of its current program and he
continued to play a role even

02:17:47.530 --> 02:17:50.940
after his retirement in 1973.

02:17:50.940 --> 02:17:53.920
Upon his retirement, Dr.
Richard Randall was appointed

02:17:53.920 --> 02:17:57.200
as the Executive Secretary
for Foreign Names and the BGN.

02:17:57.200 --> 02:18:02.080
He was the steward of foreign names
and an admirable leader of the work

02:18:02.080 --> 02:18:05.730
of the BGN for the next 20 years.

02:18:05.730 --> 02:18:09.350
With the transfer of the
Foreign Names activities in 1968,

02:18:09.350 --> 02:18:13.000
the foundation for the
modern day BGN had been laid.

02:18:16.040 --> 02:18:19.940
The evolution of the U.S. Board
on Geographic Names has progressed

02:18:19.940 --> 02:18:24.390 position:56%
from Theodore Roosevelt's Geographic
Board through increased interaction

02:18:24.390 --> 02:18:27.060
with state and international
naming authorities

02:18:27.060 --> 02:18:30.220
to massive support of
World War II efforts.

02:18:30.220 --> 02:18:33.940
It's been established,
reorganized, abolished,

02:18:33.940 --> 02:18:36.760
absorbed, and reestablished.

02:18:36.760 --> 02:18:39.090
Its focus has changed
from dealing only

02:18:39.090 --> 02:18:41.940
with unsettled questions
concerning geographic names

02:18:41.940 --> 02:18:44.920
to rendering thousands of decisions

02:18:44.920 --> 02:18:47.690
that span the Earth,
Sea, and Antarctic.

02:18:47.690 --> 02:18:54.170
It now deals with 50 states, 195
countries, and dozens of languages.

02:18:54.170 --> 02:18:57.550
The BGN has adapted to
vast technological changes

02:18:57.550 --> 02:19:00.430
with 2.7 million domestic names

02:19:00.430 --> 02:19:07.840 position:56%
and 9.8 million foreign names online
available at a few keystrokes.

02:19:07.840 --> 02:19:10.860
It has indeed been a
journey down a long, winding,

02:19:10.860 --> 02:19:13.410
and sometimes weary road.

02:19:13.410 --> 02:19:18.050
In closing, I congratulate the
U.S. Board in Geographic Name,

02:19:18.050 --> 02:19:21.050
its members and staff,
both past and present,

02:19:21.050 --> 02:19:25.090
on 125 years of providing
outstanding national

02:19:25.090 --> 02:19:28.240
and international leadership
and the standardization

02:19:28.240 --> 02:19:30.290
of geographic nomenclature.

02:19:30.290 --> 02:19:32.090
Thank you.

02:19:32.090 --> 02:19:42.110
[ Applause ]

02:19:42.110 --> 02:19:43.410
It's gone now.

02:19:43.410 --> 02:19:44.710
&gt;&gt; Here we go.

02:19:44.710 --> 02:19:46.010
Dave.

02:19:46.010 --> 02:19:47.310
&gt;&gt; Do we have any questions?

02:19:49.190 --> 02:19:52.650
It's been an interesting
history and thank you so much

02:19:52.650 --> 02:19:54.780
for sharing a long-time
[inaudible] but.

02:19:54.780 --> 02:19:56.080
Well, we do have a question.

02:19:56.080 --> 02:19:57.380
Yes. Please stand.

02:19:57.380 --> 02:19:58.680
Thank you.

02:19:58.680 --> 02:20:05.510
&gt;&gt; With the recent surge for
deleting Denali and other --

02:20:05.510 --> 02:20:10.560
[ Inaudible Speaker ]

02:20:10.560 --> 02:20:29.590 position:56%
-- do you see the movement where the
Board's facing the next 125 years

02:20:29.590 --> 02:20:34.330
of renaming what was named
in the past 125 as well

02:20:34.330 --> 02:20:36.380
as continuing on [inaudible]?

02:20:36.380 --> 02:20:37.680
&gt;&gt; Sandra Shaw: Well,
that's a good --

02:20:37.680 --> 02:20:39.370
&gt;&gt; Repeat the question.

02:20:39.370 --> 02:20:45.620 position:56%
&gt;&gt; Sandra Shaw: She wanted to know
if the names that have been approved

02:20:45.620 --> 02:20:50.650
in the last 125 years,
if we're faced

02:20:50.650 --> 02:20:52.290
with renaming some of the names.

02:20:52.290 --> 02:20:53.590
Is that correct?

02:20:53.590 --> 02:20:54.890
&gt;&gt; Yeah.

02:20:54.890 --> 02:20:56.190
&gt;&gt; Sandra Shaw: Yes.

02:20:56.190 --> 02:20:57.490
Well, I think this question
was sort of asked earlier also.

02:20:57.490 --> 02:21:00.100
I'm not quite sure about
how many renamings.

02:21:00.100 --> 02:21:01.690
I think that with -- of course,

02:21:01.690 --> 02:21:05.920
on the foreign names side you
will always have issues that --

02:21:05.920 --> 02:21:08.900
with countries changing of --
with the Soviet Union like right

02:21:08.900 --> 02:21:10.420
when it broke up, many
of the other countries

02:21:10.420 --> 02:21:15.020
that were becoming independent,
you would have naming changes.

02:21:15.020 --> 02:21:20.780
In many instances governments
themselves will change a name

02:21:20.780 --> 02:21:26.540
and require, say, the Department
of State to use a name approved.

02:21:26.540 --> 02:21:32.430
Such one issue was with the
Ivory Coast many years ago.

02:21:32.430 --> 02:21:34.280
The Ivory Coast insisted

02:21:34.280 --> 02:21:37.400
for diplomatic purposes
we use Cote d'Ivoire,

02:21:37.400 --> 02:21:40.260
the French form, which we did.

02:21:40.260 --> 02:21:43.170
However, we did approve
a conventional form

02:21:43.170 --> 02:21:46.150
for U.S. Government mapping.

02:21:46.150 --> 02:21:51.790
On the domestic name side,
it's a little more emotional.

02:21:51.790 --> 02:21:57.060
When I was Chair of the Board, it
was interesting because I worked

02:21:57.060 --> 02:22:01.690
on only foreign names and, of
course, we had always had issues

02:22:01.690 --> 02:22:05.390
with countries that wanted
us to do certain things.

02:22:05.390 --> 02:22:09.600
Usually, if we had established
diplomatic relations with them,

02:22:09.600 --> 02:22:13.600
we would accept what
they wanted us to do.

02:22:13.600 --> 02:22:18.600
But at the encouragement
of Don Orth,

02:22:18.600 --> 02:22:22.900
he got me involved
in domestic names.

02:22:22.900 --> 02:22:27.520
I was not aware of the
emotions that were involved

02:22:27.520 --> 02:22:31.900
in naming domestic features.

02:22:31.900 --> 02:22:39.670
It's really a different issue
on both sides of the house.

02:22:39.670 --> 02:22:49.860
But I can't see us going in and
renaming masses of names that --

02:22:49.860 --> 02:22:53.020
that's all I can say
on that I guess.

02:22:53.020 --> 02:22:54.320
It's [laughter].

02:22:54.320 --> 02:22:55.620
&gt;&gt; Thank you.

02:22:55.620 --> 02:22:57.570
Do we have any other questions?

02:22:57.570 --> 02:22:58.870
&gt;&gt; Douglas Caldwell: Good.

02:22:58.870 --> 02:23:01.910
At this time, what
we'd like to do is --

02:23:01.910 --> 02:23:05.830
you've heard the names of
several people mentioned.

02:23:05.830 --> 02:23:10.250
These people -- the
Board is many things.

02:23:10.250 --> 02:23:13.830
It represents the Federal
Government.

02:23:13.830 --> 02:23:16.080
It represents different agencies.

02:23:16.080 --> 02:23:20.580
But it's really the people
behind it who make it work.

02:23:20.580 --> 02:23:24.540
Now I'd like to take a few
minutes to introduce you to some

02:23:24.540 --> 02:23:31.250
of those people, particularly
our distinguished leaders.

02:23:31.250 --> 02:23:35.560
You've heard the name Don Orth
mentioned several times today.

02:23:35.560 --> 02:23:37.780
Don, could you raise your hand?

02:23:37.780 --> 02:23:39.580
Okay.

02:23:39.580 --> 02:23:47.360
[ Applause ]

02:23:47.360 --> 02:23:49.610
So Don has worked with
Geographic Names

02:23:49.610 --> 02:23:53.800
at the U.S. Geological
Survey starting in 1959,

02:23:53.800 --> 02:23:55.920
and he was the Executive Secretary

02:23:55.920 --> 02:24:01.830
for Domestic Names
from 1973 to 1990.

02:24:01.830 --> 02:24:08.440
The Executive Secretaries are
our senior staff positions.

02:24:08.440 --> 02:24:12.420 position:56%
He consolidated the working policies
of the Domestic Names Committee

02:24:12.420 --> 02:24:16.840
into the principles, policies,
and procedures that we use today.

02:24:16.840 --> 02:24:19.320
He signed the Transboundary
Agreement with Canada,

02:24:19.320 --> 02:24:24.450
and he directed the production
of a number of gazetteers.

02:24:24.450 --> 02:24:29.730 position:56%
As if he wasn't busy enough, he also
authored a very interesting history

02:24:29.730 --> 02:24:31.830
of the BGN and its evolution,

02:24:31.830 --> 02:24:34.620
some of the things
that we've heard about.

02:24:34.620 --> 02:24:37.500
One of his best-known
publications, <i>The Dictionary</i>

02:24:37.500 --> 02:24:41.750
<i>of Alaska Place Names</i>
was published in 1971.

02:24:41.750 --> 02:24:46.700
It's known by many
people simply as "Orth."

02:24:46.700 --> 02:24:52.110 position:56%
It has been referred to as the Bible
for Geographic Names in Alaska.

02:24:52.110 --> 02:24:57.650 position:56%
I have heard it said that there are
people in Alaska who have two books,

02:24:57.650 --> 02:25:00.160
the Bible and Orth [laughter].

02:25:03.310 --> 02:25:06.840
The next person I'd like to
acknowledge is Mr. Roger Payne.

02:25:06.840 --> 02:25:08.640
Roger, could you stand up.

02:25:08.640 --> 02:25:18.320
[ Applause ]

02:25:18.320 --> 02:25:20.360
Roger worked at the
U.S. Geological Survey

02:25:20.360 --> 02:25:25.340
with Geographic Names
from 1974 to 2006.

02:25:25.340 --> 02:25:30.820 position:56%
He served as the Executive Secretary
for Domestic Names from 1990

02:25:30.820 --> 02:25:40.040 position:56%
to 2006, and the Executive Secretary
of the entire BGN from 1993 to 2006.

02:25:40.040 --> 02:25:44.890
As if Roger couldn't get enough,
he currently serves as Secretary

02:25:44.890 --> 02:25:48.020
for the Advisory Committee
on Undersea Feature Names,

02:25:48.020 --> 02:25:51.480
even though he's retired --
Antarctic names, sorry, sorry.

02:25:51.480 --> 02:25:53.080
Got that wrong.

02:25:53.080 --> 02:25:54.550
Roger -- sorry about that.

02:25:54.550 --> 02:25:57.690
Roger is the father of the
Geographic Names Information System

02:25:57.690 --> 02:26:03.600
or GNIS which led the BGN from the
age of print to its digital future.

02:26:03.600 --> 02:26:08.260
