03:13:36.010 --> 03:13:38.630
that comes from the
authoritative source.

03:13:38.630 --> 03:13:41.920
There are data stewards, this
is the entity within that source

03:13:41.920 --> 03:13:44.070
that has a responsibility
for collecting data.

03:13:44.070 --> 03:13:47.550
That's often confused with
the authoritative data source.

03:13:47.550 --> 03:13:51.100
And then you've got certified
data and uncertified data.

03:13:51.100 --> 03:13:54.830
Certified data is data that's been
vetted by an authoritative source

03:13:54.830 --> 03:13:58.520
and has legal standing,
that's really important.

03:13:58.520 --> 03:14:03.480
The name has legal standing for
-- between federal agencies,

03:14:03.480 --> 03:14:05.440
not necessarily the state
governments or anybody else,

03:14:05.440 --> 03:14:08.160
but it does have legal
standing for --

03:14:08.160 --> 03:14:10.840
between federal agencies,
the place name.

03:14:10.840 --> 03:14:13.880
There's uncertified data, which
you kind of think of is either data

03:14:13.880 --> 03:14:15.510
that hasn't been quite
vetted yet, has --

03:14:15.510 --> 03:14:16.960
hasn't been anointed

03:14:16.960 --> 03:14:21.870
or its supporting data
for those place names.

03:14:21.870 --> 03:14:27.530
Okay, the volunteer data
sphere has two types of --

03:14:27.530 --> 03:14:30.090
I kind of use the notion
of friendship

03:14:30.090 --> 03:14:31.390
because that's what you're dealing

03:14:31.390 --> 03:14:33.410
with when you're working
with volunteers.

03:14:33.410 --> 03:14:36.160
There's two types of data sources,
I call them strangers of the night

03:14:36.160 --> 03:14:39.170
and friendships of utility.

03:14:39.170 --> 03:14:42.040
There is shadow sources,
we used to --

03:14:42.040 --> 03:14:45.160
we used this in partial data
all the time and we were talking

03:14:45.160 --> 03:14:48.220
at lunch how it comes
-- how people are --

03:14:48.220 --> 03:14:50.110
take government data and
then provide it to you,

03:14:50.110 --> 03:14:52.590
and then you have no idea
where this came from.

03:14:52.590 --> 03:14:54.880
You have no idea the
currency of the data.

03:14:54.880 --> 03:14:58.840 position:56%
We call that the sources, the shadow
source, the data is shadow data

03:14:58.840 --> 03:15:01.340
because you really don't
know what that data is.

03:15:01.340 --> 03:15:03.300
There's no way to confirm it.

03:15:03.300 --> 03:15:06.280
Whereas, your friends
are trusted sources.

03:15:06.280 --> 03:15:09.580
This is an entity whose
trust has been earned.

03:15:09.580 --> 03:15:11.060
Please note that.

03:15:11.060 --> 03:15:15.960
Trusted data is data from outside
the authorized process whose

03:15:15.960 --> 03:15:20.550 position:56%
limitations, currency and attributes
can be known and verified.

03:15:20.550 --> 03:15:27.040
Okay, now in the volunteer sphere,

03:15:28.130 --> 03:15:34.820
I have identified three
types of volunteers.

03:15:34.820 --> 03:15:37.970
There's the Type I and II.

03:15:37.970 --> 03:15:39.470
These have infrastructure.

03:15:39.470 --> 03:15:44.130 position:56%
The Type III are the true
volunteers, when you think about it,

03:15:44.130 --> 03:15:45.700
and these have no infrastructure.

03:15:45.700 --> 03:15:49.100
The Type I, these are
intergovernmental cooperatives.

03:15:49.100 --> 03:15:51.760
There might be something signed
where you have some people

03:15:51.760 --> 03:15:53.640
with an organization, they're
working with other people

03:15:53.640 --> 03:15:56.420
and other organizations to kind
of help pull things together.

03:15:56.420 --> 03:16:00.180
You have Type II or
indirect management support

03:16:00.180 --> 03:16:03.330
where an entity -- or where
your boss just tells you, "Well,

03:16:03.330 --> 03:16:06.560
it'd be nice if you could find time
to work on this, but you've got

03:16:06.560 --> 03:16:07.860 position:56%
to get your other stuff done first,"

03:16:07.860 --> 03:16:10.160
and there's no task
involved with that.

03:16:10.160 --> 03:16:14.950
The Type III are individuals that
are outside of the infrastructure

03:16:14.950 --> 03:16:18.730
and their participation
is altruistic.

03:16:18.730 --> 03:16:20.670
One of the big difference
between the Type I and II

03:16:20.670 --> 03:16:23.570
and the Type III is that Type I and
Type II have a paycheck coming in

03:16:23.570 --> 03:16:26.320
and the other folks don't.

03:16:26.320 --> 03:16:27.770
It's a big deal.

03:16:27.770 --> 03:16:32.310
So this is a -- the next
slide shows what it's like.

03:16:32.310 --> 03:16:33.940
We have some sort of
legislative authority

03:16:33.940 --> 03:16:36.790 position:56%
or executive authority that's
provided to an authoritative source.

03:16:36.790 --> 03:16:40.680
In this case I would
say it's the USGS.

03:16:40.680 --> 03:16:41.980
The data steward is BGN.

03:16:41.980 --> 03:16:45.820 position:56%
And then you have GNIS, the
Geographic Names Information System,

03:16:45.820 --> 03:16:50.160
is a processing system that goes
into the authoritative data bucket.

03:16:50.160 --> 03:16:51.720
The GNIS database.

03:16:51.720 --> 03:16:54.710
And out comes the authoritative
data.

03:16:54.710 --> 03:16:58.390
Now the VGI, the volunteer sphere,

03:16:58.390 --> 03:17:00.660
what you have over on
the other side is --

03:17:00.660 --> 03:17:02.900
oh, I need to mention
the one on the bottom.

03:17:02.900 --> 03:17:07.500 position:56%
You have shadow sources and see that
verboten symbol down at the bottom.

03:17:07.500 --> 03:17:11.300
Okay, now what -- doesn't
happen very often

03:17:11.300 --> 03:17:14.630
and it's not very efficient is when
somebody comes from the outside

03:17:14.630 --> 03:17:17.840
and just out of the blue they
provide you with something and say,

03:17:17.840 --> 03:17:20.680
"Well, here, what about this one?"

03:17:20.680 --> 03:17:24.530
That's not where the majority
of the information comes from.

03:17:24.530 --> 03:17:26.730
What happens is always --

03:17:26.730 --> 03:17:29.440
I mean I've looked at some
of the research that's done,

03:17:29.440 --> 03:17:32.830
and they may not like talk about
it, when you go and you look at it,

03:17:32.830 --> 03:17:37.050
there's some funding that goes to
some sort of coordinating entity.

03:17:37.050 --> 03:17:40.120
And in our case, it's
the National Map Corps.

03:17:40.120 --> 03:17:42.780
And what happens is
you have a -- in --

03:17:42.780 --> 03:17:45.710
a shadow source that
comes into the system,

03:17:45.710 --> 03:17:50.130
they provide shadow source
data, which is vetted,

03:17:50.130 --> 03:17:52.030
there's usually an
overhead for that,

03:17:52.030 --> 03:17:54.920
it goes into your trusted bucket,
and then it could be pumped

03:17:54.920 --> 03:17:58.680
into the GNIS processing system.

03:17:58.680 --> 03:18:02.510
And then you have trusted
sources who can go directly

03:18:02.510 --> 03:18:05.700
into your data bucket, or almost
directly into the data bucket,

03:18:05.700 --> 03:18:09.650
and then pumped over into
it, with much less overhead.

03:18:09.650 --> 03:18:12.260
And one of the jobs of the
coordinators is to get people

03:18:12.260 --> 03:18:15.590
to volunteer and the
second one is to move people

03:18:15.590 --> 03:18:18.990
from your shadow sources
to your trusted sources.

