03:19:52.020 --> 03:19:54.650
Now, let's look at coordinators

03:19:54.650 --> 03:19:57.490
and leaders' relationships
to the volunteers.

03:19:57.490 --> 03:20:01.090 position:56%
Your job is to create
authoritative data using volunteers.

03:20:01.090 --> 03:20:02.390
You're a coordinator.

03:20:02.390 --> 03:20:03.690
How are you going to do that?

03:20:03.690 --> 03:20:04.990
What tools do you have?

03:20:04.990 --> 03:20:07.060
You have no authority
over the volunteers except

03:20:07.060 --> 03:20:10.950
to tell them to not participate.

03:20:10.950 --> 03:20:17.070
You have no funds and you can't
give them timeout [laughter].

03:20:17.070 --> 03:20:19.930
So what can you do?

03:20:19.930 --> 03:20:25.140
Okay, now this is something
I always found very valuable.

03:20:25.140 --> 03:20:28.050
A manager's job is to make it
possible for their employees

03:20:28.050 --> 03:20:30.540
or volunteers to do a good job.

03:20:30.540 --> 03:20:34.520
If you ain't doing that, you're
not necessarily a good manager

03:20:34.520 --> 03:20:36.130
as far as I'm concerned.

03:20:36.130 --> 03:20:39.590
I've worked under a number
of them, and you know,

03:20:39.590 --> 03:20:42.550
yeah if you've got a paycheck
coming in, yeah, you'll stay there

03:20:42.550 --> 03:20:44.810
for a while, but you'll be going
looking for something else.

03:20:44.810 --> 03:20:50.310
If you're a volunteer, you're going
to be there for about a minute.

03:20:50.310 --> 03:20:52.930
So, there's three things you
can work on as a coordinator,

03:20:52.930 --> 03:20:56.050
and that is motivation,
quality assurance,

03:20:56.050 --> 03:21:01.210
and working towards improving
the number of trusted sources.

03:21:03.350 --> 03:21:06.810
Okay, so let's first look at
motivating your communities.

03:21:06.810 --> 03:21:08.670
And you'll notice,
I keep circling back

03:21:08.670 --> 03:21:11.300
because there's these concepts kind
of overlap and build on themselves,

03:21:11.300 --> 03:21:16.100
it's almost like a Venn diagram,
