03:50:02.020 --> 03:50:05.530
Prompted by a desire to share
their scientific interests, ideas,

03:50:05.530 --> 03:50:07.790
and findings, the 33 founders

03:50:07.790 --> 03:50:10.870
of the National Geographic Society
first met in the Cosmos Club

03:50:10.870 --> 03:50:16.040
in Washington D.C. on
January 13th, 1888.

03:50:16.040 --> 03:50:21.670
Among them were four men; John
Wesley Powell, Henry Gunnett,

03:50:21.670 --> 03:50:25.960
Marcus Baker, and Herbert G. Ogden.

03:50:25.960 --> 03:50:28.120
Powell played a key role
in promoting the creation

03:50:28.120 --> 03:50:32.100
of a special government board
to deal with geographic names.

03:50:32.100 --> 03:50:36.560
Two years later, Henry Gunnett, the
father of government cartography,

03:50:36.560 --> 03:50:42.430
along with Ogden and Baker
would be among the first members

03:50:42.430 --> 03:50:43.960
of a board created for the purpose

03:50:43.960 --> 03:50:48.400 position:56%
of standardizing geographic names
throughout the executive departments

03:50:48.400 --> 03:50:52.950
of the government, the U.S.
Board on Geographic Names.

03:50:52.950 --> 03:50:55.410
In the beginning, National
Geographic relied

03:50:55.410 --> 03:50:59.830
on cartographic houses to produce
most of its maps, like the Russia

03:50:59.830 --> 03:51:05.380
in Europe inset in the
January 1898 issue.

03:51:05.380 --> 03:51:09.200
[Inaudible] source on
this map was its producer,

03:51:09.200 --> 03:51:12.290
Dodd Mead and Company publishers.

03:51:15.530 --> 03:51:18.890
Place name conventions were first
addressed in the August 1890 issue

03:51:18.890 --> 03:51:20.870 position:56%
of the National Geographic Magazine.

03:51:20.870 --> 03:51:24.340
Herbert G. Ogden, now a
Society vice president,

03:51:24.340 --> 03:51:27.830
and Marcus Baker contributed
to an article entitled,

03:51:27.830 --> 03:51:30.620
"A Geographic Nomenclature."

03:51:30.620 --> 03:51:32.650
Of [inaudible] was there suggestion

03:51:32.650 --> 03:51:35.500
that a board should be formed
consisting of representatives

03:51:35.500 --> 03:51:38.360
from the different departments
and bureaus in Washington.

03:51:38.360 --> 03:51:42.350
They issued maps, charts, and
other publications requiring

03:51:42.350 --> 03:51:44.790
geographic names.

03:51:44.790 --> 03:51:46.680
This issue also contained
an appendix

03:51:46.680 --> 03:51:50.530
which presented the British,
French and German systems

03:51:50.530 --> 03:51:55.300 position:56%
for the autography and pronunciation
of foreign geographic names.

03:51:55.300 --> 03:51:59.050
It also stated that all Society
publications would follow the rules

03:51:59.050 --> 03:52:04.930
adopted in 1855 by the Royal
Geographical Society in London.

03:52:04.930 --> 03:52:10.030
Later, in April 30th, 1891,
Herbert G. Ogden reported

03:52:10.030 --> 03:52:12.610
on President Harrison's
creation of the U.S. Board

03:52:12.610 --> 03:52:17.600
on Geographic Names on
September 4th, 1890.

03:52:17.600 --> 03:52:19.930
Interesting enough,
Ogden titled the piece,

03:52:19.930 --> 03:52:23.230
"The American Board
of Geographic Names."

03:52:23.230 --> 03:52:26.230
It addressed the composition of
the board, 10 representatives

03:52:26.230 --> 03:52:28.660
from different departments
and bureaus of the government,

03:52:28.660 --> 03:52:32.100
and included its first bulletin,
which announced the adoption

03:52:32.100 --> 03:52:34.780
of the English system for the
treatment of foreign place names

03:52:34.780 --> 03:52:38.770
and transliterations
into Roman characters.

03:52:38.770 --> 03:52:42.960
In the July 1986 issue,
Henry Gunnett expounded

03:52:42.960 --> 03:52:45.780
on the accomplishments of
the board, noting the number

03:52:45.780 --> 03:52:48.140 position:56%
of meetings it had held to date, 48,

03:52:48.140 --> 03:52:53.100
and the number of decided
cases, 2835.

03:52:53.100 --> 03:52:55.740
He also defended the
board from its detractors,

03:52:55.740 --> 03:52:59.070
noting that geographic names
may be broadly distinguished

03:52:59.070 --> 03:53:03.650
into two classes, "Those which
are established by local usage,

03:53:03.650 --> 03:53:07.250
and those which are
not so established."

03:53:07.250 --> 03:53:10.800
[Laughter] I had to read
