03:55:01.840 --> 03:55:03.980
in Eastern Asia was republished

03:55:03.980 --> 03:55:08.670
as a ready reference feature
in the March 1904 issue.

03:55:08.670 --> 03:55:12.530
The editor justified it's
inclusion by stating that,

03:55:12.530 --> 03:55:16.390 position:56%
"The breaking out of the war between
Russia and Japan is bringing trouble

03:55:16.390 --> 03:55:18.570
to every household in the land.

03:55:18.570 --> 03:55:21.510
For place names of Korea and
Manchuria are spelled differently

03:55:21.510 --> 03:55:24.990
by different newspapers,
and on different maps.

03:55:24.990 --> 03:55:27.740
A system which is simple,
easy of application,

03:55:27.740 --> 03:55:30.990
and which if generally followed
reduces these variations

03:55:30.990 --> 03:55:32.720
of spellings to a minimum.

03:55:32.720 --> 03:55:34.890
Therefore, use this guide."

03:55:34.890 --> 03:55:39.240
The March 1905 issue
continued a lengthy article

03:55:39.240 --> 03:55:41.520
on the [inaudible] history
of the United States.

03:55:41.520 --> 03:55:44.340
Its aim was to let the readers
know that among the best ways

03:55:44.340 --> 03:55:49.880 position:56%
to determine the history of a place,
be it a region, city, mountain,

03:55:49.880 --> 03:55:52.670
or body of water, was by its name.

03:55:52.670 --> 03:55:56.130
A premise that still
holds true today.

03:55:56.130 --> 03:56:00.250
While the July 1905 issue contained
a listing of the board's decisions

03:56:00.250 --> 03:56:03.910
from April through June of that
year, it would be the first

03:56:03.910 --> 03:56:05.750
and last time the decisions

03:56:05.750 --> 03:56:08.350
on foreign names would
appear in the magazine.

03:56:08.350 --> 03:56:11.940
On occasion the magazine
notified its readers

03:56:11.940 --> 03:56:14.210
of key board related events.

03:56:14.210 --> 03:56:17.710
Here, President Roosevelt's
January 1906 extension

03:56:17.710 --> 03:56:23.740
of the board's responsibility was
duly noted in the March 1906 issue.

03:56:23.740 --> 03:56:25.940
In the July 1906 issue,

03:56:25.940 --> 03:56:30.150
which featured the first wildlife
photograph, signaled a start

03:56:30.150 --> 03:56:33.510
of the magazine's move from
a purely scientific journal

03:56:33.510 --> 03:56:36.930
to becoming an illustrated
monthly magazine.

03:56:36.930 --> 03:56:42.420
To this end, the March 1907 issue
was the last to carry decisions

03:56:42.420 --> 03:56:46.800
on the United States
Geographic Board.

03:56:46.800 --> 03:56:49.960
Three years after it's
formation, in March 1915,

03:56:49.960 --> 03:56:54.500 position:56%
National Geographic's Map Department
published its first map supplement,

03:56:54.500 --> 03:56:56.970
the Western Theatre of War.

03:56:56.970 --> 03:57:01.410
It was described and promoted
as, "Presenting a complete

03:57:01.410 --> 03:57:05.420
and authoritative survey
of all places, forests

03:57:05.420 --> 03:57:07.440
and river systems figuring

03:57:07.440 --> 03:57:11.440
in the [inaudible] dispatches
from the western front."

03:57:11.440 --> 03:57:14.660
Among the sources used to produce
this map insert were official maps

03:57:14.660 --> 03:57:17.110
of the French and Belgium
Departments of War,

03:57:17.110 --> 03:57:20.490
with place name assistance
from the board.

03:57:20.490 --> 03:57:23.230
Adherence to the board's
policy was not only prevalent

03:57:23.230 --> 03:57:27.680 position:56%
in place name usage in the Society's
second insert map of Africa,

03:57:27.680 --> 03:57:30.040
but in its equivalence
table as well.

03:57:30.040 --> 03:57:31.740
The table emphasized the use

03:57:31.740 --> 03:57:35.320
of the board's approved
British transliteration system,

03:57:35.320 --> 03:57:37.060
and the spelling of native names,

03:57:37.060 --> 03:57:41.230
and in expressing the English sound
equivalence of French, Italian

03:57:41.230 --> 03:57:42.810
and Portuguese spellings.

03:57:42.810 --> 03:57:45.900
Soon our other maps would
follow his convention,

03:57:45.900 --> 03:57:48.460
including our first Political Map

03:57:48.460 --> 03:57:52.740
of the World published
in December of 1922.

03:57:52.740 --> 03:57:56.490
The December 1944 issue of the
Society's new map supplement

03:57:56.490 --> 03:57:59.750
of the Soviet Union boasted
that it was the first

03:57:59.750 --> 03:58:02.450
and only available detailed
map of Soviet Russia

03:58:02.450 --> 03:58:04.670
with place names in English.

03:58:04.670 --> 03:58:06.640
It promoted the fact
that the spelling of more

03:58:06.640 --> 03:58:09.920
than 8000 place names with
the English alphabet was

03:58:09.920 --> 03:58:14.050
in itself a formidable task,
a task made much easier

03:58:14.050 --> 03:58:15.710
with the assistance of the board.

03:58:15.710 --> 03:58:21.820 position:56%
In 1958 [inaudible] 70th anniversary
of the Society's founding,

03:58:21.820 --> 03:58:23.310
a new map series was started

03:58:23.310 --> 03:58:27.420
in which the entire world
was mapped, region by region.

03:58:27.420 --> 03:58:29.510
The maps in this series
would eventually evolve

03:58:29.510 --> 03:58:32.080
into [inaudible] published in the
first edition Atlas of the World

03:58:32.080 --> 03:58:35.230
in 1963, and would go on to serve

03:58:35.230 --> 03:58:39.250
as a cartographic platform
for all future editions.

03:58:39.250 --> 03:58:43.430
Per Society policy, both the
domestic and foreign name branches

03:58:43.430 --> 03:58:44.950
of the board were consulted

03:58:44.950 --> 03:58:49.170
on appropriate place
name usage on all plates.

03:58:49.170 --> 03:58:52.960
In announcing the publication
the revised sixth edition Atlas,

03:58:52.960 --> 03:58:56.610
the November 1992 geographica
feature noted

03:58:56.610 --> 03:59:01.830
that every map naming any part
of either Yugoslavia or the USSR,

03:59:01.830 --> 03:59:04.320
even a map of Alaska, which
shares the Bering Straits

03:59:04.320 --> 03:59:06.240
with Russia, changed.

03:59:06.240 --> 03:59:11.450
And here's where I vividly
recall a former geographer,

03:59:11.450 --> 03:59:14.790 position:56%
Ted Dakara [assumed spelling], going
to BGN offices on a weekly basis

03:59:14.790 --> 03:59:18.270
and coming back with reams and
reams of place name changes,

03:59:18.270 --> 03:59:21.780
and the new countries
of Eastern Europe.

03:59:21.780 --> 03:59:27.210
This is the way we used to do place
name changes in the past, by hand.

03:59:27.210 --> 03:59:29.270
Slow and meticulous process.

03:59:29.270 --> 03:59:33.760
The 1990s witnessed the
introduced a new feature titled,

03:59:33.760 --> 03:59:35.060
"Behind the Scenes."

03:59:35.060 --> 03:59:37.940
It was intended to provide our
readers with an inside look

03:59:37.940 --> 03:59:40.830 position:56%
into the workings of the geographic.

03:59:40.830 --> 03:59:44.950
The November 1995 issue contained a
piece on Kazakhstan's new spelling

03:59:44.950 --> 03:59:46.970
as confirmed by the board.

03:59:46.970 --> 03:59:49.950
Ironically, after changing our
maps to reflect the new spelling,

03:59:49.950 --> 03:59:53.650
and promoting this piece,
the ancient Kazakhstan was

03:59:53.650 --> 03:59:55.880
to be restored a mere two
years later [laughter].

03:59:55.880 --> 04:00:01.460
As you've seen the Society's first
began disseminating BGN approved

04:00:01.460 --> 04:00:04.970
place names in its journals quickly
to be followed by its supplement,

04:00:04.970 --> 04:00:10.270
page maps, globes, atlases, apps
and other cartographic products,

04:00:10.270 --> 04:00:15.860
including our giant traveling maps
for students, which averaging 26

04:00:15.860 --> 04:00:20.530
by 35 feet in size, are the
largest maps we have ever produced.

04:00:20.530 --> 04:00:22.750
Our cartographic line
still adheres to some

04:00:22.750 --> 04:00:25.530
of the place name conventions
whose origins can be traced back

04:00:25.530 --> 04:00:28.640
to the early day sort of the
U.S. Board on Geographic Names,

04:00:28.640 --> 04:00:31.750
including the prolific use
of conventional place names

04:00:31.750 --> 04:00:35.340
for cultural and physical features.

04:00:35.340 --> 04:00:39.270
For shared geographic features.

04:00:39.270 --> 04:00:42.830
For variant place names.

04:00:42.830 --> 04:00:46.170
For transliterated place names.

04:00:46.170 --> 04:00:50.540
As well as for contentious
place names.

04:00:50.540 --> 04:00:52.770
Today the collaboration
between the Society

04:00:52.770 --> 04:00:55.280
and the board remains
as strong as ever.

04:00:55.280 --> 04:00:58.050
Any pertinent information
that we obtain,

04:00:58.050 --> 04:01:01.520
in this case the Cuban
